{"title_page": "Pavao An\u0111eli\u0107", "text_new": "{{short description|Archaeologist and historian from Bosnia}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{more citations needed|date=August 2019}}{{notability|1=Academics|date=August 2019}}}}\n\n'''Pavao An\u0111eli\u0107''' (1920-1985) was a [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian]] [[lawyer]], [[Archaeology|archeologist]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=s1MLAQAAIAAJ&q=%22pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87%22&dq=%22pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiNuaX-0PHlAhUNl4sKHW-nBs84ChDoAQhpMAg|title=Anali|last=Hercegovine|first=Zemaljski muzej Bosne i|date=1938|publisher=Muzej.|language=hr}}</ref> and [[History|historian]]. He mainly studied the history of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina in the Middle Ages|medieval Bosnia]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kurtovi\u0107|first=Esad|title=Pavao An\u0111eli\u0107|url=https://www.academia.edu/31210031/Pavao_An%C4%91eli%C4%87|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kurtovi\u0107|first=Esad|title=Hercegovac u srcu Bosne. Visoko i njegova okolina u djelu Pava An\u0111eli\u0107a, Most XXVI/127 (38), Mostar 2000, 92-94.|url=https://www.academia.edu/31209354/Hercegovac_u_srcu_Bosne._Visoko_i_njegova_okolina_u_djelu_Pava_An%C4%91eli%C4%87a_Most_XXVI_127_38_Mostar_2000_92-94|language=en}}</ref> and is noted for archeological work done at [[Mile (Visoko)|Mile]], near [[Visoko]] and Kraljeva Sutjeska and Bobovac.{{sfn|Vego|1982|p=84}}\n\nHe was born in [[Sulti\u0107i]], [[Konjic]]. Completed Franciscan gymnasium in [[Visoko]] and later law in [[Zagreb]], studied history in [[Sarajevo]]. He worked in Institute for the Protection of Cultural Monuments in Sarajevo, and was higher custodian in the [[National Museum of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in Sarajevo until his retirement. Achieved doctorate at [[University of Belgrade Faculty of Philosophy]]. His archaeological research was concentrated at royal court sites of medieval Bosnia on [[Bobovac]] and [[Kraljeva Sutjeska]], and in the area of [[Visoko during the Middle Ages|Visoko]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/645706424|title=Zbornik o Pavlu An\u0111eli\u0107u|date=2008|publisher=Franjeva\u010dka teologija Sarajevo|others=An\u0111eli\u0107, Pavao., Karamati\u0107, Marko.|isbn=9789958742088|location=Sarajevo|oclc=645706424}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enciklopedija.hr/natuknica.aspx?id=2687|title=An\u0111eli\u0107, Pavao {{!}} Hrvatska enciklopedija|website=www.enciklopedija.hr|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=f0u3AAAAIAAJ&q=an%C4%91eli%C4%87+tvrtko&dq=an%C4%91eli%C4%87+tvrtko&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwju-JCS9fDlAhWQlYsKHch5CuwQ6AEIOTAC|title=Anali Zavoda za povijesne znanosti Jugoslavenske akademije znanosti i umjetnosti u Dubrovniku|date=1990|publisher=Akademija|language=hr}}</ref> He received \"27 July Award\" in 1974 from [[Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|SR BiH]] for his contributions in archeological works conducted in Bobovac and Kraljeva Sutjeska.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1974-07-15|title=Republi\u010dka nagrada BIH|url=https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=215856|journal=Informatica museologica|language=hr|volume=5|issue=25|pages=28\u20130|issn=0350-2325}}</ref>\n\n== Books ==\n\n* Bobovac and Kraljeva Sutjeska: Royal seats of Bosnian rulers in 14 and 15 centuries (''Bobovac i Kraljeva Sutjeska: stolna mjesta bosanskih vladara u XIV i XV stolje\u0107u'')<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=QIcDAAAAMAAJ&q=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&dq=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV-dOZpODlAhUElIsKHeOxBcoQ6AEIVzAG|title=Bobovac i Kraljeva Sutjeska: stolna mjesta bosanskih vladara u XIV i XV stolje\u0107u|last=An\u0111eli\u0107|first=Pavao|date=1973|publisher=Veselin Masle\u0161a|language=hr}}</ref>\n* Studies about territorial and political organization of medieval Bosnia (''Studije o teritorijalnopoliti\u010dkoj organizaciji srednjovjekovne Bosne'')<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=v-jKMgEACAAJ&dq=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV-dOZpODlAhUElIsKHeOxBcoQ6AEIOTAC|title=Studije o teritorijalnopoliti\u010dkoj organizaciji srednjovjekovne Bosne|last=An\u0111eli\u0107|first=Pavao|date=1982|publisher=\"Svjetlost,\" OOUR Izdava\u010dka djelatnost|language=en}}</ref>\n* Visoko and environment through history (''Visoko i okolina kroz istoriju'')<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=oc0qAAAAMAAJ&q=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&dq=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV-dOZpODlAhUElIsKHeOxBcoQ6AEIKjAA|title=Visoko i okolina kroz istoriju|last=An\u0111eli\u0107|first=Pavao|date=1984|publisher=Skup\u0161tina op\u0161tine Visoko|language=hr}}</ref>\n\n== Literature ==\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=7sFpAAAAMAAJ&dq=pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87+tvrtko&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87+|title=Postanak srednjovjekovne bosanske dr\u017eave|last=Vego|first=Marko|publisher=Svjetlost, Sarajevo|year=1982|isbn=|editor-last=|editor-first=|editorlink=Marko Vego|edition=|location=Sarajevo|pages=84|ref=|orig-year=1982}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andelic, Pavao}}\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina historians]]\n[[Category:People from Konjic]]\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n\n\n{{BosniaHerzegovina-scientist-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Archaeologist and historian from Bosnia}}\n{{Multiple issues|{{refimprove|date=August 2019}}{{notability|1=Academics|date=August 2019}}}}\n\n'''Pavao An\u0111eli\u0107''' (1920-1985) was a [[Bosnia and Herzegovina|Bosnian]] [[lawyer]], [[Archaeology|archeologist]]<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=s1MLAQAAIAAJ&q=%22pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87%22&dq=%22pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87%22&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiNuaX-0PHlAhUNl4sKHW-nBs84ChDoAQhpMAg|title=Anali|last=Hercegovine|first=Zemaljski muzej Bosne i|date=1938|publisher=Muzej.|language=hr}}</ref> and [[History|historian]]. He mainly studied the history of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina in the Middle Ages|medieval Bosnia]]<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kurtovi\u0107|first=Esad|title=Pavao An\u0111eli\u0107|url=https://www.academia.edu/31210031/Pavao_An%C4%91eli%C4%87|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite journal|last=Kurtovi\u0107|first=Esad|title=Hercegovac u srcu Bosne. Visoko i njegova okolina u djelu Pava An\u0111eli\u0107a, Most XXVI/127 (38), Mostar 2000, 92-94.|url=https://www.academia.edu/31209354/Hercegovac_u_srcu_Bosne._Visoko_i_njegova_okolina_u_djelu_Pava_An%C4%91eli%C4%87a_Most_XXVI_127_38_Mostar_2000_92-94|language=en}}</ref> and is noted for archeological work done at [[Mile (Visoko)|Mile]], near [[Visoko]] and Kraljeva Sutjeska and Bobovac.{{sfn|Vego|1982|p=84}}   \n\nHe was born in [[Sulti\u0107i]], [[Konjic]]. Completed Franciscan gymnasium in [[Visoko]] and later law in [[Zagreb]], studied history in [[Sarajevo]]. He worked in Institute for the Protection of Cultural Monuments in Sarajevo, and was higher custodian in the [[National Museum of Bosnia and Herzegovina]] in Sarajevo until his retirement. Achieved doctorate at [[University of Belgrade Faculty of Philosophy]]. His archaeological research was concentrated at royal court sites of medieval Bosnia on [[Bobovac]] and [[Kraljeva Sutjeska]], and in the area of [[Visoko during the Middle Ages|Visoko]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://www.worldcat.org/oclc/645706424|title=Zbornik o Pavlu An\u0111eli\u0107u|date=2008|publisher=Franjeva\u010dka teologija Sarajevo|others=An\u0111eli\u0107, Pavao., Karamati\u0107, Marko.|isbn=9789958742088|location=Sarajevo|oclc=645706424}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.enciklopedija.hr/natuknica.aspx?id=2687|title=An\u0111eli\u0107, Pavao {{!}} Hrvatska enciklopedija|website=www.enciklopedija.hr|access-date=2019-09-02}}</ref><ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=f0u3AAAAIAAJ&q=an%C4%91eli%C4%87+tvrtko&dq=an%C4%91eli%C4%87+tvrtko&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwju-JCS9fDlAhWQlYsKHch5CuwQ6AEIOTAC|title=Anali Zavoda za povijesne znanosti Jugoslavenske akademije znanosti i umjetnosti u Dubrovniku|date=1990|publisher=Akademija|language=hr}}</ref> He received \"27 July Award\" in 1974 from [[Socialist Republic of Bosnia and Herzegovina|SR BiH]] for his contributions in archeological works conducted in Bobovac and Kraljeva Sutjeska.<ref>{{Cite journal|date=1974-07-15|title=Republi\u010dka nagrada BIH|url=https://hrcak.srce.hr/index.php?show=clanak&id_clanak_jezik=215856|journal=Informatica museologica|language=hr|volume=5|issue=25|pages=28\u20130|issn=0350-2325}}</ref>  \n\n== Books ==\n\n* Bobovac and Kraljeva Sutjeska: Royal seats of Bosnian rulers in 14 and 15 centuries (''Bobovac i Kraljeva Sutjeska: stolna mjesta bosanskih vladara u XIV i XV stolje\u0107u'')<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=QIcDAAAAMAAJ&q=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&dq=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV-dOZpODlAhUElIsKHeOxBcoQ6AEIVzAG|title=Bobovac i Kraljeva Sutjeska: stolna mjesta bosanskih vladara u XIV i XV stolje\u0107u|last=An\u0111eli\u0107|first=Pavao|date=1973|publisher=Veselin Masle\u0161a|language=hr}}</ref>\n* Studies about territorial and political organization of medieval Bosnia (''Studije o teritorijalnopoliti\u010dkoj organizaciji srednjovjekovne Bosne'')<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=v-jKMgEACAAJ&dq=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV-dOZpODlAhUElIsKHeOxBcoQ6AEIOTAC|title=Studije o teritorijalnopoliti\u010dkoj organizaciji srednjovjekovne Bosne|last=An\u0111eli\u0107|first=Pavao|date=1982|publisher=\"Svjetlost,\" OOUR Izdava\u010dka djelatnost|language=en}}</ref>\n* Visoko and environment through history (''Visoko i okolina kroz istoriju'')<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=oc0qAAAAMAAJ&q=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&dq=Pavao+An%C4%91eli%C4%87&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwiV-dOZpODlAhUElIsKHeOxBcoQ6AEIKjAA|title=Visoko i okolina kroz istoriju|last=An\u0111eli\u0107|first=Pavao|date=1984|publisher=Skup\u0161tina op\u0161tine Visoko|language=hr}}</ref>\n\n== Literature ==\n\n* {{Cite book|url=https://books.google.ba/books?id=7sFpAAAAMAAJ&dq=pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87+tvrtko&focus=searchwithinvolume&q=pavao+an%C4%91eli%C4%87+|title=Postanak srednjovjekovne bosanske dr\u017eave|last=Vego|first=Marko|publisher=Svjetlost, Sarajevo|year=1982|isbn=|editor-last=|editor-first=|editorlink=Marko Vego|edition=|location=Sarajevo|pages=84|ref=|orig-year=1982}}\n\n== References ==\n<references />\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Andelic, Pavao}}\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina archaeologists]]\n[[Category:Bosnia and Herzegovina historians]]\n[[Category:People from Konjic]]\n\n[[Category:1920 births]]\n[[Category:1985 deaths]]\n\n\n{{BosniaHerzegovina-scientist-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Pavao_An%C4%91eli%C4%87"}
{"title_page": "George Frederic Watts", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{distinguish|George Fiddes Watt}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name        = George Frederic Watts\n| image       = Watts George Frederic.jpeg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=yes|1817|02|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Marylebone]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1904|7|1|1817|2|23}}\n| death_place = [[London]], England\n| nationality = British\n| field       = Painting, sculpture\n| training    = [[William Behnes]]<br />[[Royal Academy of Arts|Royal Academy]]\n| movement    = [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist]]\n| works       = ''[[Hope (painting)|Hope]]''<br />''Love and Life''<br />''[[Physical Energy (sculpture)|Physical Energy]]''\n| patrons     = [[Alexander Constantine Ionides]]\n| awards      = [[Order of Merit]]\n}}\n[[File:Miss May Prinsep by George Frederic Watts.jpeg|thumb|''[[Prinsep|Miss May Prinsep]]'']]\n\n'''George Frederic Watts''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit|OM]] [[List of Royal Academicians|RA]]}} (23 February 1817, in [[London]] \u2013 1 July 1904) was a British painter and sculptor associated with the [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist]] movement. He said \"I paint ideas, not things.\"<ref name=ELS /> Watts became famous in his lifetime for his allegorical works, such as ''[[Hope (painting)|Hope]]'' and ''Love and Life''. These paintings were intended to form part of an epic symbolic cycle called the \"House of Life\", in which the emotions and aspirations of life would all be represented in a universal symbolic language.\n\n== Life ==\nWatts was born in [[Marylebone]] in central London on the birthday of [[George Frederic Handel]] (after whom he was named), to the second wife of a poor piano-maker. Delicate in health and with his mother dying while he was still young, he was home-schooled by his father in a conservative interpretation of Christianity as well as via the classics such as the ''[[Iliad]].''  The former put him off conventional religion for life, while the latter was a continual influence on his art. He showed artistic promise very early, learning sculpture from the age of 10 with [[William Behnes]], starting to study devotedly the [[Elgin Marbles]] (later writing \"It was from them alone that I learned\") and then enrolling as a student at the [[Royal Academy of Arts|Royal Academy]] at the age of 18. He first exhibited at the Academy in 1837.<ref name=ELS>[[Edward Lucie-Smith|Lucie-Smith, Edward.]] (1972) ''Symbolist Art''. London: [[Thames & Hudson]], p. 47. {{ISBN|0-500-20125-0}}</ref> He also began his portraiture career, receiving patronage from his close contemporary [[Alexander Constantine Ionides]], who later came to be a close friend.\n\nHe came to the public eye with a drawing entitled ''Caractacus'', which was entered for a competition to design murals for the new [[Palace of Westminster#Frescoes|Houses of Parliament]] at [[City of Westminster|Westminster]] in 1843. Watts won a first prize in the competition, which was intended to promote narrative paintings on patriotic subjects, appropriate to the nation's legislature. In the end Watts made little contribution to the Westminster decorations, but from it he conceived his vision of a building covered with murals representing the spiritual and social evolution of humanity.<ref>The complex history surrounding the decoration is best summarized by\n[[T. S. R. Boase]], ''The Decorations of the New Palace of Westminster 1841\u20131863'', in: ''Journal of the [[Warburg Institute|Warburg]] and [[Courtauld Institute|Courtauld]] Institutes'' 17:1954, pp. 319\u201358.</ref>\n\nThe prize from the Westminster competition did, however, fund a long visit to Italy from 1843 onwards, where Watts stayed and became friends with the British ambassador [[Henry Fox, 4th Baron Holland]] and his wife [[Augusta Fox, Baroness Holland|Augusta]] at their homes in [[Casa Feroni]] and the [[Villa Careggi]]. Also while in Italy Watts began producing landscapes and was inspired by [[Michelangelo]]'s [[Sistine Chapel]] and [[Giotto di Bondone|Giotto]]'s [[Scrovegni Chapel]]. In 1847, while still in Italy, Watts entered a new competition for the Houses of Parliament with his image of [[Alfred the Great]], ''Alfred Inciting the Saxons to Prevent the Landing of the Danes by Encountering them at Sea'', on a patriotic subject but using [[Phideas|Phidean]] inspiration. Leaving Florence in April 1847 for what was intended to be a brief return to London, he ended up staying. Back in Britain he was unable to obtain a building in which to carry out his plan of a grand fresco based on his Italian experiences, though he did produce a 45&nbsp;ft by 40&nbsp;ft fresco on the upper part of the east wall of the Great Hall of [[Lincoln's Inn]] entitled ''Justice, A Hemicycle of Lawgivers'' (completed 1859), inspired by [[Raphael]]'s ''[[The School of Athens]]''. In consequence most of his major works are conventional oil paintings, some of which were intended as studies for the House of Life.\n\nIn his studio he met [[Henry Thoby Prinsep]] (for 16 years a member of the [[Council of India]]) and his wife Sara (n\u00e9e Pattle). Watts thus joined the [[Prinsep]] circle of [[bohemianism|bohemians]], including Sara's seven sisters (including Virginia, with whom Watts fell in love but who married [[Charles Somers-Cocks, 3rd Earl Somers|Charles, Viscount Eastnor]] in 1850), and [[Julia Margaret Cameron]]. Previously staying at 48 Cambridge Street, and then in Mayfair, in 1850 he helped the Prinseps into a 21-year lease on [[Little Holland House]], and stayed there with them and their [[salon (gathering)|salon]] for the next 21 years. (The building was the dower house on the Hollands' London estate in [[Kensington]], near the house of [[Frederic Leighton, 1st Baron Leighton|Lord Leighton]].)\n\nOne of only two pupils Watts ever accepted was Henry's son [[Valentine Cameron Prinsep]]; the other was [[John Roddam Spencer Stanhope]] \u2013 both remained friends, but neither became a major artist.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gbTd5_RuzisC&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=%22virginia+woolf%22+%22john+prinsep%22&source=web&ots=8MIvC8zgm2&sig=E6CiJ7PMAQLCKzCra2kdZMiMOg0&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=5&ct=result|title=Clouds}}</ref> While living as tenant at Little Holland House, Watts's epic paintings were exhibited in [[Whitechapel]] by his friend the social reformer Canon [[Samuel Barnett (reformer)|Samuel Barnett]], and he finally received a commission for the Houses of Parliament, completing his ''The Triumph of the Red Cross Knight'' (from ''[[The Faerie Queene]]'') in 1852\u201353. He also took a short trip back to Italy in 1853 (including Venice, where Titian became yet more of an inspiration) and with [[Charles Thomas Newton]] to excavate [[Halicarnassus]] in 1856\u201357, via Constantinople and the Greek islands.\n\nIn the 1860s, Watts' work shows the influence of [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti|Rossetti]], often emphasising sensuous pleasure and rich colour. Among these paintings is a portrait of his young wife, the actress [[Ellen Terry]], who was 30 years his junior \u2013 having been introduced by mutual friend [[Tom Taylor]], they married on 20 February 1864, just seven days short of her 17th birthday. When she eloped with another man after less than a year of marriage, Watts was obliged to divorce her. Watts's association with Rossetti and the [[Aesthetic movement]] altered during the 1870s, as his work increasingly combined [[Classicism|Classical]] traditions with a deliberately agitated and troubled surface, to suggest the dynamic energies of life and evolution, as well as the tentative and transitory qualities of life. These works formed part of a revised version of the House of Life, influenced by the ideas of [[Max M\u00fcller]], the founder of [[comparative religion]]. Watts hoped to trace the evolving \"mythologies of the races [of the world]\" in a grand synthesis of spiritual ideas with modern science, especially [[Darwinian]] evolution.\n[[File:Assistants and George Frederic Watts - Hope - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|upright|''[[Hope (painting)|Hope]]'', painted in 1886 and given to the nation in 1897]]\n\nWith the lease on Little Holland House nearing its end and the building soon to be demolished, in the early 1870s he commissioned a new London home nearby from [[C. R. Cockerell]]: New Little Holland House (backing onto the estate of Lord Leighton), and acquired a house at [[Freshwater, Isle of Wight]] \u2013 his friends Julia Margaret Cameron and [[Lord Tennyson]] already had homes on the island. To maintain his friendship with the Prinsep family as their children began leaving home, he built The Briary for them near Freshwater, and adopted their relative [[Blanche Clogstoun]]. In 1877, his [[decree nisi]] from Ellen Terry finally came through, and the [[Grosvenor Gallery]] was opened by his friend [[Coutts Lindsay]]. This was to prove his ideal venue for the next ten years.\n\nIn 1886, at the age of 69, Watts remarried, to [[Mary Fraser Tytler]], a Scottish designer and potter, then aged 36. In 1891 he bought land near [[Compton, Guildford|Compton]], south of [[Guildford]], in [[Surrey]]. The couple named the house \"Limnerslease\" (combining the words \"limner\" or artist with \"leasen\" or glean) and built the [[Watts Gallery]] nearby, a museum dedicated to his work \u2013 the first (and now the only) purpose-built gallery in Britain devoted to a single artist \u2013 which opened in April 1904, shortly before his death, and received a major expansion between 2006 and 2011.\n\nWatts's wife Mary had designed the nearby earlier [[Watts Mortuary Chapel]], which Watts paid for; he also painted a version of ''[[The All-Pervading]]'' for the [[altar]] only three months before he died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.compton-surrey.co.uk/#/wattschapel/4518411494|title=Watts Chapel|publisher=compton-surrey.co.uk|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> Both Limnerslease and the chapel are now maintained, and the house owned, by the Watts Gallery. In 2016 Watts' studio in the house re-opened, restored as far as possible using photographs from Watts' lifetime, as part of the Watts Gallery, and the main residential section can be visited on a guided tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wattsgallery.org.uk/en-gb/about-us/artists-village/watts-studios/|title=Watts Studios \u2013 Watts Gallery|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nMany of his paintings are owned by [[Tate Britain]] \u2013 he donated 18 of his symbolic paintings to Tate in 1897, and three more in 1900. Some of these have been loaned to the Watts Gallery in recent years, and are on display there.\n\nRefusing the baronetcy twice offered him by [[Queen Victoria]], he was elected as an Academician to the Royal Academy in 1867 and accepted to be one of the original members of the new [[Order of Merit]] (OM) in 1902 \u2013 in his own words, on behalf of all English artists. The order was announced in the [[1902 Coronation Honours]] list published on 26 June 1902,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Coronation Honours |day_of_week=Thursday |date=26 June 1902 |page_number=5 |issue=36804| }}</ref> and he received the insignia from King [[Edward VII]] at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 8 August 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court Circular |day_of_week=Saturday |date=9 August 1902 |page_number=6 |issue=36842| }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27470|page=5679|date=2 September 1902|}}</ref>\n[[File:Cape Town Rhodes memorial energy statue.jpg|thumb|upright|Detail of ''[[Physical Energy (sculpture)|Physical Energy]]'' at [[Rhodes Memorial]] in [[Cape Town]], South Africa.]]\nIn his late paintings, Watts' creative aspirations mutate into mystical images such as ''The Sower of the Systems'', in which Watts seems to anticipate [[abstract art]]. This painting depicts God as a barely visible shape in an energised pattern of stars and nebulae. Some of Watts' other late works also seem to anticipate the paintings of [[Picasso's Blue Period]]. He was also admired as a portrait painter. His portraits were of the most important men and women of the day, intended to form a \"House of Fame\". Many of these are now in the collection of the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]]: 17 were donated in 1895, with more than 30 more added subsequently. In his portraits Watts sought to create a tension between disciplined stability and the power of action. He was also notable for emphasising the signs of strain and wear on his sitter's faces. Sitters included [[Charles Dilke]], [[Thomas Carlyle]] , [[James Martineau]], and [[William Morris]].\n\n===''Physical Energy''===\n\nAlthough best known as a painter, Watts was also a sculptor. He began work on the plaster model for ''Physical Energy'' (Watts Gallery) around 1883 and was still working on it at the time of his death in 1904. In that year the first bronze cast of the work became the artist's last submission to the Royal Academy's summer exhibition. It marked a new prominence for the courtyard of Burlington House as a site for dramatic contemporary sculpture, a role continued today by the Annenberg Courtyard. ''Physical Energy'' is an allegory of the human need for new challenges \u2013 of our instinct to always be scanning the horizon, looking towards the future. Watts said it is \"a symbol of that restless physical impulse to seek the still unachieved in the domain of material things\".\n\n''Physical Energy'' was the culmination of Watts's ambition in the field of public sculpture, embodying the artist's belief that access to great art would bring immense benefits to the country at large. Having completed a commission for the [[Hugh Grosvenor, 1st Duke of Westminster|Duke of Westminster]] for an equestrian monument to commemorate his ancestor, [[Hugh d'Avranches, Earl of Chester|Hugh Lupus]], in 1883 Watts set to work on a new plaster model of another horse and rider, without specific reference to any individual. Reinvigorating the rhetoric of the equestrian monument for the modern age, Watts conceived ''Physical Energy'' as an allegory of human vitality and humanity's ceaseless struggle for betterment.\n\nThe plaster model of ''Physical Energy'' was part of the artist's bequest to Watts Gallery upon his death in 1904. The first bronze cast of the model, made in 1902 at the Parlanti Foundry<ref>The Illustrated London News October 3rd 1903 p484\n</ref>, was exhibited in the courtyard of the Royal Academy in 1904, as part of the annual Summer Exhibition. It then travelled to Cape Town to form part of a memorial to the founder of Rhodesia (now [[Zimbabwe]]), [[Cecil Rhodes]].  In 1907, a posthumous cast was made and sited in Kensington Gardens, London, fulfilling the artist's intention to gift the work to the British Government, insisting that it should be \"for the nation\" and displayed \"somewhere in London\". A third cast, created in 1959, is situated in the grounds of the [[National Archives of Zimbabwe]] in [[Harare]].\n\n== Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice ==\n{{Main|Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice}}\n[[File:George Frederic Watts - The Minotaur - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''The Minotaur'', 1885]]\nAn admirer of royalty \u2013 he had painted [[Fran\u00e7ois d'Orl\u00e9ans, Prince of Joinville|Prince de Joinville]] and Edward, Prince of Wales \u2013 Watts proposed, in 1887, to commemorate the [[Golden Jubilee of Queen Victoria]] by creating a Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice to commemorate ordinary people who had died saving the lives of others, and who might otherwise have been forgotten. The scheme was not accepted at that time, but in 1898 Watts was approached by [[Henry Gamble]], the vicar of [[St Botolph's Aldersgate]] church. He suggested the memorial could be created in [[Postman's Park]] in the [[City of London]].\n\nThe memorial was unveiled in an unfinished state in 1900, consisting of a 50-foot (15&nbsp;m) wooden loggia designed by Ernest George, sheltering a wall with space for 120 ceramic memorial tiles to be designed and made by [[William De Morgan]]. At the time of opening, only four of the memorial tiles were in place. Watts died in 1904, and his widow Mary Watts took over the running of the project.\n\n== Reception ==\nSeveral reverent biographies of Watts were written shortly after his death. With the emergence of [[Modernism]], however, his reputation declined. [[Virginia Woolf]]'s comic play ''Freshwater'' portrays him in a satirical manner, an approach also adopted by [[Wilfrid Jasper Walter Blunt|Wilfred Blunt]], former curator of the Watts Gallery, in his irreverent 1975 biography ''England's Michelangelo''. In his 1988 book on [[John Ruskin|Ruskin]], the art critic [[Peter Fuller]] emphasised Watts's spiritual and stylistic importance, also noting that late post-symbolist works such as ''The Sower of the Systems'' \"stretched beyond the brink of abstraction\".<ref>Fuller, Peter. ''Theoria: Art and the Absence of Grace''. London, Chatto and Windus, 1988.</ref> On the centenary of his death Veronica Franklin Gould published ''G.F. Watts: The Last Great Victorian'', a positive study of his life and work.\n\nThe composer [[Charles Villiers Stanford]] wrote his Sixth Symphony \"In Memoriam G. F. Watts\". It was composed in 1905 and first performed on 18 January 1906 in London under Stanford's direction. The four movements, although not having a detailed programme, are inspired by several works of art by Watts.\n\nLiterary references to Watts and his work include [[Elizabeth Taylor (novelist)|Elizabeth Taylor]]'s 1953 novel ''[[Angel (novel)|Angel]]'', where a picture by Watts is donated to a provincial museum by the protagonist, and mention of Watts' painting ''Progress'' in ''Bella Donna'' by [[Robert Smythe Hichens|Robert Hichens]] (1909, p.&nbsp;34). Watts features (not altogether favourably) as a character in [[Lynne Truss]]'s comic novel ''Tennyson's Gift'' (1996).\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery heights=\"200\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:George Frederick Watts, 1860-62, Sir Galahad, oil on canvas, 191.8 x 107 cm, Harvard Art Museums, Fogg Museum.jpg|''Sir [[Galahad]]''\nFile:George Frederick Watts 001.jpg|''Self-portrait''\nFile:Watts-Paolo and Francesca.jpg|''Paolo and Francesca''\nFile:George Frederic Watts, Fata Morgana.jpg|''[[Morgan le Fay|Fata Morgana]]''\nFile:Watts George Frederic Orpheus And Eurydice.jpg|''Orpheus And Eurydice''\nFile:Watts George Frederic The Judgement Of Paris.jpg|''The Judgement of Paris''\nFile:George Meredith by George Frederic Watts.jpg|''Portrait of [[George Meredith]]''\nFile:Physical Energy, Kensington.jpg|''[[Physical Energy (sculpture)|Physical Energy]]''\nFile:Dante Gabriel Rossetti by George Frederic Watts.jpg|''[[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]]''\nFile:Henry Thoby Prinsep by George Frederic Watts.jpeg|''[[Henry Thoby Prinsep]]''\nFile:Self portrait by George Frederic Watts 1864.jpeg|''Self-Portrait'', 1864\nFile:Sir Leslie Stephen by George Frederic Watts 1878.jpeg|''Sir [[Leslie Stephen]]'', 1878\nFile:Watts marie fox.jpg|''[[Marie Fox|Miss Mary Fox]], with Spanish Pointer'', c. 1854\nFile:The wounded heron.jpg|''The wounded heron'', 1837 ([[Watts Gallery]])\nFile:Good Samaritan (Watts).jpg|''The [[Parable of the Good Samaritan|Good Samaritan]]''\nFile:George Frederic Watts by George Andrews.jpg|Portrait by [[Louis Deuchars|L. R. Deuchars]]\nFile:Dame (Alice) Ellen Terry ('Choosing') by George Frederic Watts.jpg|''Choosing'' ([[Ellen Terry]]), ca. 1864\nFile:EB1911 Plate V. v24, pg.506, Fig 3.jpg|The bust of [[Clytie (Oceanid)|Clytie]]\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Discovering the Sculptures of George Frederick Watts O.M., R.A.'' (1994) BY Elizabeth Hutchings {{ISBN|0-9521939-6-5}}\n* ''The Laurel and the Thorn; A Study of G. F. Watts'' (1945) by Ronald Chapman, Faber and Faber Ltd.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Art UK bio}}\n*{{ODNBweb|id=36781|title=Watts, George Frederic}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/programmes/restoration/2006/se_watts_gallery_01.shtml BBC Restoration Appeal for the Watts Gallery]\n*[http://www.wattsgallery.org.uk/ The Watts Gallery, Compton]\n*[http://www.georgefredericwatts.org/ georgefredericwatts.org], 392 works by George Frederic Watts\n{{Gutenberg|no=13477|name=Watts (1817\u20131904) by William Loftus Hare}}, with eight reproductions in colour. (by [[William Loftus Hare]])\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091002222535/http://www.tate.org.uk/learning/worksinfocus/watts/ Watts \u2013 5 works in focus] at Tate Online\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/live/watts.asp G.F. Watts: Portraits, Fame & Beauty in Victorian Society], 2004\u201305 exhibition at the National Portrait Gallery\n\n{{George Frederic Watts}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watts, George Frederic}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Marylebone]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English sculptors]]\n[[Category:Religious artists]]\n[[Category:English male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Symbolist painters]]\n[[Category:Symbolist sculptors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Artists' Rifles soldiers]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n[[Category:Royal Society of Portrait Painters]]\n[[Category:Academic art]]\n[[Category:20th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Athenaeum Club, London]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=July 2016}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2016}}\n{{distinguish|George Fiddes Watt}}\n{{Infobox artist\n| name        = George Frederic Watts\n| image       = Watts George Frederic.jpeg\n| caption     = \n| birth_date  = {{birth date|df=yes|1817|02|23}}\n| birth_place = [[Marylebone]], [[Middlesex]], England\n| death_date  = {{death date and age|df=yes|1904|7|1|1817|2|23}}\n| death_place = [[London]], England\n| nationality = British\n| field       = Painting, sculpture\n| training    = [[William Behnes]]<br />[[Royal Academy of Arts|Royal Academy]]\n| movement    = [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist]]\n| works       = ''[[Hope (painting)|Hope]]''<br />''Love and Life''<br />''[[Physical Energy (sculpture)|Physical Energy]]''\n| patrons     = [[Alexander Constantine Ionides]]\n| awards      = [[Order of Merit]]\n}}\n[[File:Miss May Prinsep by George Frederic Watts.jpeg|thumb|''[[Prinsep|Miss May Prinsep]]'']]\n\n'''George Frederic Watts''' {{Post-nominals|post-noms=[[Order of Merit|OM]] [[List of Royal Academicians|RA]]}} (23 February 1817, in [[London]] \u2013 1 July 1904) was a British painter and sculptor associated with the [[Symbolism (arts)|Symbolist]] movement. He said \"I paint ideas, not things.\"<ref name=ELS /> Watts became famous in his lifetime for his allegorical works, such as ''[[Hope (painting)|Hope]]'' and ''Love and Life''. These paintings were intended to form part of an epic symbolic cycle called the \"House of Life\", in which the emotions and aspirations of life would all be represented in a universal symbolic language.\n\n== Life ==\nWatts was born in [[Marylebone]] in central London on the birthday of [[George Frederic Handel]] (after whom he was named), to the second wife of a poor piano-maker. Delicate in health and with his mother dying while he was still young, he was home-schooled by his father in a conservative interpretation of Christianity as well as via the classics such as the ''[[Iliad]].''  The former put him off conventional religion for life, while the latter was a continual influence on his art. He showed artistic promise very early, learning sculpture from the age of 10 with [[William Behnes]], starting to study devotedly the [[Elgin Marbles]] (later writing \"It was from them alone that I learned\") and then enrolling as a student at the [[Royal Academy of Arts|Royal Academy]] at the age of 18. He first exhibited at the Academy in 1837.<ref name=ELS>[[Edward Lucie-Smith|Lucie-Smith, Edward.]] (1972) ''Symbolist Art''. London: [[Thames & Hudson]], p. 47. {{ISBN|0-500-20125-0}}</ref> He also began his portraiture career, receiving patronage from his close contemporary [[Alexander Constantine Ionides]], who later came to be a close friend.\n\nHe came to the public eye with a drawing entitled ''Caractacus'', which was entered for a competition to design murals for the new [[Palace of Westminster#Frescoes|Houses of Parliament]] at [[City of Westminster|Westminster]] in 1843. Watts won a first prize in the competition, which was intended to promote narrative paintings on patriotic subjects, appropriate to the nation's legislature. In the end Watts made little contribution to the Westminster decorations, but from it he conceived his vision of a building covered with murals representing the spiritual and social evolution of humanity.<ref>The complex history surrounding the decoration is best summarized by\n[[T. S. R. Boase]], ''The Decorations of the New Palace of Westminster 1841\u20131863'', in: ''Journal of the [[Warburg Institute|Warburg]] and [[Courtauld Institute|Courtauld]] Institutes'' 17:1954, pp. 319\u201358.</ref>\n\nThe prize from the Westminster competition did, however, fund a long visit to Italy from 1843 onwards, where Watts stayed and became friends with the British ambassador [[Henry Fox, 4th Baron Holland]] and his wife [[Augusta Fox, Baroness Holland|Augusta]] at their homes in [[Casa Feroni]] and the [[Villa Careggi]]. Also while in Italy Watts began producing landscapes and was inspired by [[Michelangelo]]'s [[Sistine Chapel]] and [[Giotto di Bondone|Giotto]]'s [[Scrovegni Chapel]]. In 1847, while still in Italy, Watts entered a new competition for the Houses of Parliament with his image of [[Alfred the Great]], ''Alfred Inciting the Saxons to Prevent the Landing of the Danes by Encountering them at Sea'', on a patriotic subject but using [[Phideas|Phidean]] inspiration. Leaving Florence in April 1847 for what was intended to be a brief return to London, he ended up staying. Back in Britain he was unable to obtain a building in which to carry out his plan of a grand fresco based on his Italian experiences, though he did produce a 45&nbsp;ft by 40&nbsp;ft fresco on the upper part of the east wall of the Great Hall of [[Lincoln's Inn]] entitled ''Justice, A Hemicycle of Lawgivers'' (completed 1859), inspired by [[Raphael]]'s ''[[The School of Athens]]''. In consequence most of his major works are conventional oil paintings, some of which were intended as studies for the House of Life.\n\nIn his studio he met [[Henry Thoby Prinsep]] (for 16 years a member of the [[Council of India]]) and his wife Sara (n\u00e9e Pattle). Watts thus joined the [[Prinsep]] circle of [[bohemianism|bohemians]], including Sara's seven sisters (including Virginia, with whom Watts fell in love but who married [[Charles Somers-Cocks, 3rd Earl Somers|Charles, Viscount Eastnor]] in 1850), and [[Julia Margaret Cameron]]. Previously staying at 48 Cambridge Street, and then in Mayfair, in 1850 he helped the Prinseps into a 21-year lease on [[Little Holland House]], and stayed there with them and their [[salon (gathering)|salon]] for the next 21 years. (The building was the dower house on the Hollands' London estate in [[Kensington]], near the house of [[Frederic Leighton, 1st Baron Leighton|Lord Leighton]].)\n\nOne of only two pupils Watts ever accepted was Henry's son [[Valentine Cameron Prinsep]]; the other was [[John Roddam Spencer Stanhope]] \u2013 both remained friends, but neither became a major artist.<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=gbTd5_RuzisC&pg=PA28&lpg=PA28&dq=%22virginia+woolf%22+%22john+prinsep%22&source=web&ots=8MIvC8zgm2&sig=E6CiJ7PMAQLCKzCra2kdZMiMOg0&hl=en&sa=X&oi=book_result&resnum=5&ct=result|title=Clouds}}</ref> While living as tenant at Little Holland House, Watts's epic paintings were exhibited in [[Whitechapel]] by his friend the social reformer Canon [[Samuel Barnett (reformer)|Samuel Barnett]], and he finally received a commission for the Houses of Parliament, completing his ''The Triumph of the Red Cross Knight'' (from ''[[The Faerie Queene]]'') in 1852\u201353. He also took a short trip back to Italy in 1853 (including Venice, where Titian became yet more of an inspiration) and with [[Charles Thomas Newton]] to excavate [[Halicarnassus]] in 1856\u201357, via Constantinople and the Greek islands.\n\nIn the 1860s, Watts' work shows the influence of [[Dante Gabriel Rossetti|Rossetti]], often emphasising sensuous pleasure and rich colour. Among these paintings is a portrait of his young wife, the actress [[Ellen Terry]], who was 30 years his junior \u2013 having been introduced by mutual friend [[Tom Taylor]], they married on 20 February 1864, just seven days short of her 17th birthday. When she eloped with another man after less than a year of marriage, Watts was obliged to divorce her. Watts's association with Rossetti and the [[Aesthetic movement]] altered during the 1870s, as his work increasingly combined [[Classicism|Classical]] traditions with a deliberately agitated and troubled surface, to suggest the dynamic energies of life and evolution, as well as the tentative and transitory qualities of life. These works formed part of a revised version of the House of Life, influenced by the ideas of [[Max M\u00fcller]], the founder of [[comparative religion]]. Watts hoped to trace the evolving \"mythologies of the races [of the world]\" in a grand synthesis of spiritual ideas with modern science, especially [[Darwinian]] evolution.\n[[File:Assistants and George Frederic Watts - Hope - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|left|upright|''[[Hope (painting)|Hope]]'', painted in 1886 and given to the nation in 1897]]\n\nWith the lease on Little Holland House nearing its end and the building soon to be demolished, in the early 1870s he commissioned a new London home nearby from [[C. R. Cockerell]]: New Little Holland House (backing onto the estate of Lord Leighton), and acquired a house at [[Freshwater, Isle of Wight]] \u2013 his friends Julia Margaret Cameron and [[Lord Tennyson]] already had homes on the island. To maintain his friendship with the Prinsep family as their children began leaving home, he built The Briary for them near Freshwater, and adopted their relative [[Blanche Clogstoun]]. In 1877, his [[decree nisi]] from Ellen Terry finally came through, and the [[Grosvenor Gallery]] was opened by his friend [[Coutts Lindsay]]. This was to prove his ideal venue for the next ten years.\n\nIn 1886, at the age of 69, Watts remarried, to [[Mary Fraser Tytler]], a Scottish designer and potter, then aged 36. In 1891 he bought land near [[Compton, Guildford|Compton]], south of [[Guildford]], in [[Surrey]]. The couple named the house \"Limnerslease\" (combining the words \"limner\" or artist with \"leasen\" or glean) and built the [[Watts Gallery]] nearby, a museum dedicated to his work \u2013 the first (and now the only) purpose-built gallery in Britain devoted to a single artist \u2013 which opened in April 1904, shortly before his death, and received a major expansion between 2006 and 2011.\n\nWatts's wife Mary had designed the nearby earlier [[Watts Mortuary Chapel]], which Watts paid for; he also painted a version of ''[[The All-Pervading]]'' for the [[altar]] only three months before he died.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.compton-surrey.co.uk/#/wattschapel/4518411494|title=Watts Chapel|publisher=compton-surrey.co.uk|accessdate=19 December 2008}}</ref> Both Limnerslease and the chapel are now maintained, and the house owned, by the Watts Gallery. In 2016 Watts' studio in the house re-opened, restored as far as possible using photographs from Watts' lifetime, as part of the Watts Gallery, and the main residential section can be visited on a guided tour.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.wattsgallery.org.uk/en-gb/about-us/artists-village/watts-studios/|title=Watts Studios \u2013 Watts Gallery|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nMany of his paintings are owned by [[Tate Britain]] \u2013 he donated 18 of his symbolic paintings to Tate in 1897, and three more in 1900. Some of these have been loaned to the Watts Gallery in recent years, and are on display there.\n\nRefusing the baronetcy twice offered him by [[Queen Victoria]], he was elected as an Academician to the Royal Academy in 1867 and accepted to be one of the original members of the new [[Order of Merit]] (OM) in 1902 \u2013 in his own words, on behalf of all English artists. The order was announced in the [[1902 Coronation Honours]] list published on 26 June 1902,<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=The Coronation Honours |day_of_week=Thursday |date=26 June 1902 |page_number=5 |issue=36804| }}</ref> and he received the insignia from King [[Edward VII]] at [[Buckingham Palace]] on 8 August 1902.<ref>{{Cite newspaper The Times |articlename=Court Circular |day_of_week=Saturday |date=9 August 1902 |page_number=6 |issue=36842| }}</ref><ref>{{London Gazette|issue=27470|page=5679|date=2 September 1902|}}</ref>\n[[File:Cape Town Rhodes memorial energy statue.jpg|thumb|upright|Detail of ''[[Physical Energy (sculpture)|Physical Energy]]'' at [[Rhodes Memorial]] in [[Cape Town]], South Africa.]]\nIn his late paintings, Watts' creative aspirations mutate into mystical images such as ''The Sower of the Systems'', in which Watts seems to anticipate [[abstract art]]. This painting depicts God as a barely visible shape in an energised pattern of stars and nebulae. Some of Watts' other late works also seem to anticipate the paintings of [[Picasso's Blue Period]]. He was also admired as a portrait painter. His portraits were of the most important men and women of the day, intended to form a \"House of Fame\". Many of these are now in the collection of the [[National Portrait Gallery, London|National Portrait Gallery]]: 17 were donated in 1895, with more than 30 more added subsequently. In his portraits Watts sought to create a tension between disciplined stability and the power of action. He was also notable for emphasising the signs of strain and wear on his sitter's faces. Sitters included [[Charles Dilke]], [[Thomas Carlyle]] , [[James Martineau]], and [[William Morris]].\n\n===''Physical Energy''===\n\nAlthough best known as a painter, Watts was also a sculptor. He began work on the plaster model for ''Physical Energy'' (Watts Gallery) around 1883 and was still working on it at the time of his death in 1904. In that year the first bronze cast of the work became the artist's last submission to the Royal Academy's summer exhibition. It marked a new prominence for the courtyard of Burlington House as a site for dramatic contemporary sculpture, a role continued today by the Annenberg Courtyard. ''Physical Energy'' is an allegory of the human need for new challenges \u2013 of our instinct to always be scanning the horizon, looking towards the future. Watts said it is \"a symbol of that restless physical impulse to seek the still unachieved in the domain of material things\".\n\n''Physical Energy'' was the culmination of Watts's ambition in the field of public sculpture, embodying the artist's belief that access to great art would bring immense benefits to the country at large. Having completed a commission for the [[Hugh Grosvenor, 1st Duke of Westminster|Duke of Westminster]] for an equestrian monument to commemorate his ancestor, [[Hugh d'Avranches, Earl of Chester|Hugh Lupus]], in 1883 Watts set to work on a new plaster model of another horse and rider, without specific reference to any individual. Reinvigorating the rhetoric of the equestrian monument for the modern age, Watts conceived ''Physical Energy'' as an allegory of human vitality and humanity's ceaseless struggle for betterment.\n\nThe plaster model of ''Physical Energy'' was part of the artist's bequest to Watts Gallery upon his death in 1904. The first bronze cast of the model, made in 1902, was exhibited in the courtyard of the Royal Academy in 1904, as part of the annual Summer Exhibition. It then travelled to Cape Town to form part of a memorial to the founder of Rhodesia (now [[Zimbabwe]]), [[Cecil Rhodes]].  In 1907, a posthumous cast was made and sited in Kensington Gardens, London, fulfilling the artist's intention to gift the work to the British Government, insisting that it should be \"for the nation\" and displayed \"somewhere in London\". A third cast, created in 1959, is situated in the grounds of the [[National Archives of Zimbabwe]] in [[Harare]].\n\n== Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice ==\n{{Main|Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice}}\n[[File:George Frederic Watts - The Minotaur - Google Art Project.jpg|thumb|''The Minotaur'', 1885]]\nAn admirer of royalty \u2013 he had painted [[Fran\u00e7ois d'Orl\u00e9ans, Prince of Joinville|Prince de Joinville]] and Edward, Prince of Wales \u2013 Watts proposed, in 1887, to commemorate the [[Golden Jubilee of Queen Victoria]] by creating a Memorial to Heroic Self-Sacrifice to commemorate ordinary people who had died saving the lives of others, and who might otherwise have been forgotten. The scheme was not accepted at that time, but in 1898 Watts was approached by [[Henry Gamble]], the vicar of [[St Botolph's Aldersgate]] church. He suggested the memorial could be created in [[Postman's Park]] in the [[City of London]].\n\nThe memorial was unveiled in an unfinished state in 1900, consisting of a 50-foot (15&nbsp;m) wooden loggia designed by Ernest George, sheltering a wall with space for 120 ceramic memorial tiles to be designed and made by [[William De Morgan]]. At the time of opening, only four of the memorial tiles were in place. Watts died in 1904, and his widow Mary Watts took over the running of the project.\n\n== Reception ==\nSeveral reverent biographies of Watts were written shortly after his death. With the emergence of [[Modernism]], however, his reputation declined. [[Virginia Woolf]]'s comic play ''Freshwater'' portrays him in a satirical manner, an approach also adopted by [[Wilfrid Jasper Walter Blunt|Wilfred Blunt]], former curator of the Watts Gallery, in his irreverent 1975 biography ''England's Michelangelo''. In his 1988 book on [[John Ruskin|Ruskin]], the art critic [[Peter Fuller]] emphasised Watts's spiritual and stylistic importance, also noting that late post-symbolist works such as ''The Sower of the Systems'' \"stretched beyond the brink of abstraction\".<ref>Fuller, Peter. ''Theoria: Art and the Absence of Grace''. London, Chatto and Windus, 1988.</ref> On the centenary of his death Veronica Franklin Gould published ''G.F. Watts: The Last Great Victorian'', a positive study of his life and work.\n\nThe composer [[Charles Villiers Stanford]] wrote his Sixth Symphony \"In Memoriam G. F. Watts\". It was composed in 1905 and first performed on 18 January 1906 in London under Stanford's direction. The four movements, although not having a detailed programme, are inspired by several works of art by Watts.\n\nLiterary references to Watts and his work include [[Elizabeth Taylor (novelist)|Elizabeth Taylor]]'s 1953 novel ''[[Angel (novel)|Angel]]'', where a picture by Watts is donated to a provincial museum by the protagonist, and mention of Watts' painting ''Progress'' in ''Bella Donna'' by [[Robert Smythe Hichens|Robert Hichens]] (1909, p.&nbsp;34). Watts features (not altogether favourably) as a character in [[Lynne Truss]]'s comic novel ''Tennyson's Gift'' (1996).\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery heights=\"200\" mode=\"packed\">\nFile:George Frederick Watts, 1860-62, Sir Galahad, oil on canvas, 191.8 x 107 cm, Harvard Art Museums, Fogg Museum.jpg|''Sir [[Galahad]]''\nFile:George Frederick Watts 001.jpg|''Self-portrait''\nFile:Watts-Paolo and Francesca.jpg|''Paolo and Francesca''\nFile:George Frederic Watts, Fata Morgana.jpg|''[[Morgan le Fay|Fata Morgana]]''\nFile:Watts George Frederic Orpheus And Eurydice.jpg|''Orpheus And Eurydice''\nFile:Watts George Frederic The Judgement Of Paris.jpg|''The Judgement of Paris''\nFile:George Meredith by George Frederic Watts.jpg|''Portrait of [[George Meredith]]''\nFile:Physical Energy, Kensington.jpg|''[[Physical Energy (sculpture)|Physical Energy]]''\nFile:Dante Gabriel Rossetti by George Frederic Watts.jpg|''[[Dante Gabriel Rossetti]]''\nFile:Henry Thoby Prinsep by George Frederic Watts.jpeg|''[[Henry Thoby Prinsep]]''\nFile:Self portrait by George Frederic Watts 1864.jpeg|''Self-Portrait'', 1864\nFile:Sir Leslie Stephen by George Frederic Watts 1878.jpeg|''Sir [[Leslie Stephen]]'', 1878\nFile:Watts marie fox.jpg|''[[Marie Fox|Miss Mary Fox]], with Spanish Pointer'', c. 1854\nFile:The wounded heron.jpg|''The wounded heron'', 1837 ([[Watts Gallery]])\nFile:Good Samaritan (Watts).jpg|''The [[Parable of the Good Samaritan|Good Samaritan]]''\nFile:George Frederic Watts by George Andrews.jpg|Portrait by [[Louis Deuchars|L. R. Deuchars]]\nFile:Dame (Alice) Ellen Terry ('Choosing') by George Frederic Watts.jpg|''Choosing'' ([[Ellen Terry]]), ca. 1864\nFile:EB1911 Plate V. v24, pg.506, Fig 3.jpg|The bust of [[Clytie (Oceanid)|Clytie]]\n</gallery>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== Bibliography ==\n* ''Discovering the Sculptures of George Frederick Watts O.M., R.A.'' (1994) BY Elizabeth Hutchings {{ISBN|0-9521939-6-5}}\n* ''The Laurel and the Thorn; A Study of G. F. Watts'' (1945) by Ronald Chapman, Faber and Faber Ltd.\n\n== External links ==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category}}\n* {{Art UK bio}}\n*{{ODNBweb|id=36781|title=Watts, George Frederic}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/history/programmes/restoration/2006/se_watts_gallery_01.shtml BBC Restoration Appeal for the Watts Gallery]\n*[http://www.wattsgallery.org.uk/ The Watts Gallery, Compton]\n*[http://www.georgefredericwatts.org/ georgefredericwatts.org], 392 works by George Frederic Watts\n{{Gutenberg|no=13477|name=Watts (1817\u20131904) by William Loftus Hare}}, with eight reproductions in colour. (by [[William Loftus Hare]])\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20091002222535/http://www.tate.org.uk/learning/worksinfocus/watts/ Watts \u2013 5 works in focus] at Tate Online\n*[http://www.npg.org.uk/live/watts.asp G.F. Watts: Portraits, Fame & Beauty in Victorian Society], 2004\u201305 exhibition at the National Portrait Gallery\n\n{{George Frederic Watts}}\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watts, George Frederic}}\n[[Category:1817 births]]\n[[Category:1904 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Marylebone]]\n[[Category:19th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English male painters]]\n[[Category:20th-century English painters]]\n[[Category:English sculptors]]\n[[Category:Religious artists]]\n[[Category:English male sculptors]]\n[[Category:Symbolist painters]]\n[[Category:Symbolist sculptors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Order of Merit]]\n[[Category:Artists' Rifles soldiers]]\n[[Category:Royal Academicians]]\n[[Category:Royal Society of Portrait Painters]]\n[[Category:Academic art]]\n[[Category:20th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:19th-century British sculptors]]\n[[Category:Members of the Athenaeum Club, London]]\n", "name_user": "Steve Parlanti", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/George_Frederic_Watts"}
{"title_page": "Vinegar Hill (Charlottesville, Virginia)", "text_new": "'''Vinegar Hill''' was one of the earliest neighborhoods in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]]. Located near downtown, it was bordered by West Main Street to the south, Preston Avenue to the north, and 4th street to the east.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.charlottesville.org/departments-and-services/departments-h-z/neighborhood-development-services/historic-preservation-and-design-review/historic-resources-committee/local-markers/vinegar-hill|title=Vinegar Hill {{!}} City of Charlottesville|website=www.charlottesville.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> When it was first populated by African American families in the early nineteenth century, it was called \"Random Row.\" George Toole, a local Irish-American resident, began calling it Vinegar Hill to memorialize the [[Battle of Vinegar Hill]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Alexander |first1=James |title=Early Charlottesville: Recollections of James Alexander, 1828-1874 |date=1942 |publisher=The Michie Company, Printers |location=Charlottesville, Virginia |page=110 |edition=2 |url=https://search.lib.virginia.edu/catalog/uva-lib:178506 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> It was incorporated into the city in 1835. '''Vinegar Hill''' is remembered now for its invasive urban renewal project begun in 1964 that razed the majority black neighborhood.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== African American community ==\nAfter the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the neighborhood became a thriving center of Charlottesville's African American community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cvilletomorrow.org/news/article/30442-vinegar-hill-park-process-to-start-this-summer/|title=Vinegar Hill Park process to start this summer \u22c5 Charlottesville Tomorrow|website=Charlottesville Tomorrow|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> In the decades when the city remained [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregated]], black-owned businesses in Vinegar Hill served the needs of Charlottesville's black community and some white customers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aahistoricsitesva.org/items/show/457|title=Vinegar Hill {{!}} African American Historic Sites Database|website=African American Historic Sites Database|language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> Although many of the structures in the neighborhood were rented to the mostly black community by white property owners, more than a quarter of the homes and business properties were black owned.<ref name=\":2\" /> Most Vinegar Hill residents lived without basic amenities like running water, plumbing, or electric. The city of Charlottesville's health council did not feel they had adequate power to enforce the standing city code that required each home to have these amenities in every home, including those in Vinegar Hill.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matthew|first=Dayna Bowen|date=1 April 2019|title=The \"Terminal Condition\" Condition in Virginia's Natural Death Act|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/1072986|journal=Virginia Law Review|volume=73|issue=4|pages=749|doi=10.2307/1072986|issn=0042-6601|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Razing and redevelopment ==\nIn 1965, the entire neighborhood was razed as part of an [[urban renewal]] plan initiated in the 1950s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://timeline.com/charlottesville-vinegar-hill-demolished-ba27b6ea69e1|title=In 1965, the city of Charlottesville demolished a thriving black neighborhood|date=2017-08-15|work=Timeline|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> One church, thirty businesses, and 158 families were displaced, almost all African American.<ref name=\":1\" /> Six hundred community members were moved into the Westhaven [[Public housing in the United States|public housing]] complex.<ref name=\":2\" /> Families who had lived in stand-alone houses now resided in multi-family complexes.<ref name=\":0\" /> The site remained vacant for well over a decade, and it was not until 1985 that a redevelopment project was put in place and the [[Omni Hotels & Resorts|Omni Hotel]] and surrounding development installed on the neighborhood's site.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLeading up to and following the \"[[Unite the Right rally|Unite the Right Rally]]\" on August 12, 2017, Vinegar Hill's destruction was a central topic of national coverage of Charlottesville's history. In June 2017, [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] published an opinion on the relationship between Vinegar Hill's destruction and the Robert E. Lee statue in nearby Lee (now [[Market Street (Charlottesville)|Market Street]], formerly Emancipation) Park.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.charlottesville.org/departments-and-services/departments-h-z/parks-recreation/parks-trails/city-parks/emancipation-park-formerly-known-as-lee-park/history-and-gardens-of-emancipation-park | title=History and Gardens of Market Street Park &#124; City of Charlottesville}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/history/2017/06/how_charlottesville_s_confederate_statues_helped_decimate_the_city_s_historically.html|title=Tools of Displacement|last=Abramowitz|first=Sophie|date=2017-06-23|work=Slate|access-date=2018-09-04|last2=Latterner|first2=Eva|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339|last3=Rosenblith|first3=Gillet}}</ref> Just three days after the rally, the website [[Medium (website)|Medium]] posted a Timeline article about Vinegar Hill,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://timeline.com/charlottesville-vinegar-hill-demolished-ba27b6ea69e1|title=In 1965, the city of Charlottesville demolished a thriving black neighborhood|date=2017-08-15|work=Timeline|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> and it was the focus of articles in the  [[The New York Times|New York Times]] and [[The Atlantic]] on August 18.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/18/us/charlottesville-racial-disparity-vinegar-hill.html|title=In Charlottesville, Some Say Statue Debate Obscures a Deep Racial Split|last=Eiigon|first=John|date=18 August 2017|work=New York Times|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/black-community-charlottesville-response/537285/|title=Black Charlottesville Has Seen This All Before|last=II|first=Vann R. Newkirk|date=2017-08-18|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Memorialization ==\nThe names \"Random Row\" and \"Vinegar Hill\" continue to be used in the area where the neighborhood once stood. Random Row Books operated on West Main Street from 2009 to 2013, when the building was razed to make way for a hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-ville.com/going-dark-theclosure-of-random-row-books-extinguishes-a-community-light/#.W4ri8n4nYWo|title=Going dark: The closure of Random Row Books extinguishes a community light - C-VILLE Weekly|date=2013-06-18|work=C-VILLE Weekly|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Random Row Brewery opened on Preston Avenue in 2016. Vinegar Hill Shopping Center operates on Preston Avenue. There has also been a clothing line named after Vinegar Hill, named Vinegar Hill Vintage. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vinegarhillvintage.com|title=Vinegar Hill Vintage}}</ref> This clothing line is also associated with the Vinegar Hill Magazine which is the only publication of record with content that covers issues focused on issues that affect African American people in Charlottesville.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vinegarhillmagazine.com|title= Vinegar Hill Magazine}}</ref>   The Vinegar Hill Theater, a small [[movie house]], operated for 37 years before closing in 2016, and has since that time operated with a variant name and different mission.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-ville.com/final-cut-charlottesvilles-last-independently-owned-movie-theater-goes-dark/#.W4rjs34nYWo|title=Charlottesville's last independently owned movie theater goes dark - C-VILLE Weekly|date=2013-08-06|work=C-VILLE Weekly|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en-US}}</ref> A [[historic marker]] telling a brief history of the neighborhood is mounted on a low wall facing Water Street on the Charlottesville Downtown Mall.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2011, the City of Charlottesville officially apologized for razing the neighborhood.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailyprogress.com/news/charlottesville-officially-apologizes-for-razing-vinegar-hill/article_83b8aed4-2f4a-5ee2-baaa-2e7c9d43c2b0.html|title=Charlottesville officially apologizes for razing Vinegar Hill|last=Moomaw|first=Graham|date=7 November 2011|work=The Daily Progress|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Charlottesville, Virginia]]\n", "text_old": "'''Vinegar Hill''' was one of the earliest neighborhoods in [[Charlottesville, Virginia]]. Located near downtown, it was bordered by West Main Street to the south, Preston Avenue to the north, and 4th street to the east.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.charlottesville.org/departments-and-services/departments-h-z/neighborhood-development-services/historic-preservation-and-design-review/historic-resources-committee/local-markers/vinegar-hill|title=Vinegar Hill {{!}} City of Charlottesville|website=www.charlottesville.org|language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> When it was first populated by African American families in the early nineteenth century, it was called \"Random Row.\" Local resident and Irish-American George Toole began calling it Vinegar Hill to memorialize the [[Battle of Vinegar Hill]].<ref>{{cite book |last1=Alexander |first1=James |title=Early Charlottesville: Recollections of James Alexander, 1828-1874 |date=1942 |publisher=The Michie Company, Printers |location=Charlottesville, Virginia |page=110 |edition=2 |url=https://search.lib.virginia.edu/catalog/uva-lib:178506 |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref> It was incorporated into the city in 1835. '''Vinegar Hill''' is remembered now for its invasive urban renewal project begun in 1964 that razed the majority black neighborhood.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\n== African American community ==\nAfter the [[American Civil War|Civil War]], the neighborhood became a thriving center of Charlottesville's African American community.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cvilletomorrow.org/news/article/30442-vinegar-hill-park-process-to-start-this-summer/|title=Vinegar Hill Park process to start this summer \u22c5 Charlottesville Tomorrow|website=Charlottesville Tomorrow|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> In the decades when the city remained [[Racial segregation in the United States|segregated]], black-owned businesses in Vinegar Hill served the needs of Charlottesville's black community and some white customers.<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.aahistoricsitesva.org/items/show/457|title=Vinegar Hill {{!}} African American Historic Sites Database|website=African American Historic Sites Database|language=en|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> Although many of the structures in the neighborhood were rented to the mostly black community by white property owners, more than a quarter of the homes and business properties were black owned.<ref name=\":2\" /> Most Vinegar Hill residents lived without basic amenities like running water, plumbing, or electric. The city of Charlottesville's health council did not feel they had adequate power to enforce the standing city code that required each home to have these amenities in every home, including those in Vinegar Hill.<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Matthew|first=Dayna Bowen|date=1 April 2019|title=The \"Terminal Condition\" Condition in Virginia's Natural Death Act|url=http://dx.doi.org/10.2307/1072986|journal=Virginia Law Review|volume=73|issue=4|pages=749|doi=10.2307/1072986|issn=0042-6601|via=}}</ref>\n\n== Razing and redevelopment ==\nIn 1965, the entire neighborhood was razed as part of an [[urban renewal]] plan initiated in the 1950s.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://timeline.com/charlottesville-vinegar-hill-demolished-ba27b6ea69e1|title=In 1965, the city of Charlottesville demolished a thriving black neighborhood|date=2017-08-15|work=Timeline|access-date=2018-09-01}}</ref> One church, thirty businesses, and 158 families were displaced, almost all African American.<ref name=\":1\" /> Six hundred community members were moved into the Westhaven [[Public housing in the United States|public housing]] complex.<ref name=\":2\" /> Families who had lived in stand-alone houses now resided in multi-family complexes.<ref name=\":0\" /> The site remained vacant for well over a decade, and it was not until 1985 that a redevelopment project was put in place and the [[Omni Hotels & Resorts|Omni Hotel]] and surrounding development installed on the neighborhood's site.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nLeading up to and following the \"[[Unite the Right rally|Unite the Right Rally]]\" on August 12, 2017, Vinegar Hill's destruction was a central topic of national coverage of Charlottesville's history. In June 2017, [[Slate (magazine)|Slate]] published an opinion on the relationship between Vinegar Hill's destruction and the Robert E. Lee statue in nearby Lee (now [[Market Street (Charlottesville)|Market Street]], formerly Emancipation) Park.<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://www.charlottesville.org/departments-and-services/departments-h-z/parks-recreation/parks-trails/city-parks/emancipation-park-formerly-known-as-lee-park/history-and-gardens-of-emancipation-park | title=History and Gardens of Market Street Park &#124; City of Charlottesville}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/news_and_politics/history/2017/06/how_charlottesville_s_confederate_statues_helped_decimate_the_city_s_historically.html|title=Tools of Displacement|last=Abramowitz|first=Sophie|date=2017-06-23|work=Slate|access-date=2018-09-04|last2=Latterner|first2=Eva|language=en-US|issn=1091-2339|last3=Rosenblith|first3=Gillet}}</ref> Just three days after the rally, the website [[Medium (website)|Medium]] posted a Timeline article about Vinegar Hill,<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite news|url=https://timeline.com/charlottesville-vinegar-hill-demolished-ba27b6ea69e1|title=In 1965, the city of Charlottesville demolished a thriving black neighborhood|date=2017-08-15|work=Timeline|access-date=2018-09-04}}</ref> and it was the focus of articles in the  [[The New York Times|New York Times]] and [[The Atlantic]] on August 18.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2017/08/18/us/charlottesville-racial-disparity-vinegar-hill.html|title=In Charlottesville, Some Say Statue Debate Obscures a Deep Racial Split|last=Eiigon|first=John|date=18 August 2017|work=New York Times|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/politics/archive/2017/08/black-community-charlottesville-response/537285/|title=Black Charlottesville Has Seen This All Before|last=II|first=Vann R. Newkirk|date=2017-08-18|work=The Atlantic|access-date=2018-09-04|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n== Memorialization ==\nThe names \"Random Row\" and \"Vinegar Hill\" continue to be used in the area where the neighborhood once stood. Random Row Books operated on West Main Street from 2009 to 2013, when the building was razed to make way for a hotel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-ville.com/going-dark-theclosure-of-random-row-books-extinguishes-a-community-light/#.W4ri8n4nYWo|title=Going dark: The closure of Random Row Books extinguishes a community light - C-VILLE Weekly|date=2013-06-18|work=C-VILLE Weekly|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en-US}}</ref> Random Row Brewery opened on Preston Avenue in 2016. Vinegar Hill Shopping Center operates on Preston Avenue. There has also been a clothing line named after Vinegar Hill, named Vinegar Hill Vintage. <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vinegarhillvintage.com|title=Vinegar Hill Vintage}}</ref> This clothing line is also associated with the Vinegar Hill Magazine which is the only publication of record with content that covers issues focused on issues that affect African American people in Charlottesville.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.vinegarhillmagazine.com|title= Vinegar Hill Magazine}}</ref>   The Vinegar Hill Theater, a small [[movie house]], operated for 37 years before closing in 2016, and has since that time operated with a variant name and different mission.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.c-ville.com/final-cut-charlottesvilles-last-independently-owned-movie-theater-goes-dark/#.W4rjs34nYWo|title=Charlottesville's last independently owned movie theater goes dark - C-VILLE Weekly|date=2013-08-06|work=C-VILLE Weekly|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en-US}}</ref> A [[historic marker]] telling a brief history of the neighborhood is mounted on a low wall facing Water Street on the Charlottesville Downtown Mall.<ref name=\":1\" /> In 2011, the City of Charlottesville officially apologized for razing the neighborhood.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailyprogress.com/news/charlottesville-officially-apologizes-for-razing-vinegar-hill/article_83b8aed4-2f4a-5ee2-baaa-2e7c9d43c2b0.html|title=Charlottesville officially apologizes for razing Vinegar Hill|last=Moomaw|first=Graham|date=7 November 2011|work=The Daily Progress|access-date=2018-09-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Charlottesville, Virginia]]\n", "name_user": "Filmnoirnic", "label": "safe", "comment": "this makes the syntax flow better", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Vinegar_Hill_(Charlottesville,_Virginia)"}
{"title_page": "Bir Tawil", "text_new": "{{redirect|Kingdom of North Sudan|other areas considered North Sudan|Sudan}}\n{{short description|Unclaimed land in Africa}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                   = Kingdom Of Navidia\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  {{lang|ar|\u0628\u064a\u0631 \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644}}\n|nickname               = KON\n|settlement_type        = Claimed land \n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = File:Topographic Map of Bir Tawil.png\n|imagesize              = 250px\n|image_caption          =[[Topographic map]] of Bir Tawil (highlighted in red)\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|pushpin_map            = Egypt#Sudan<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location between Egypt and Sudan\n|pushpin_map_alt        = Neither Egypt nor Sudan claim Bir Tawil, which is located between the two countries.\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Terra nullius|None]]\n|subdivision_type1      =\n|subdivision_name1      =\n|subdivision_type2      =\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude           =\n|unit_pref                = metric\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 2060\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of                = 2018\n|population_footnotes            =\n|population_note                 = No permanent populations.\n|population_total                = 0\n|population_density_sq_mi        = \n|population_metro                = \n|population_density_metro_km2    =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi  =\n|population_blank1_title         = Ethnicities\n|population_blank1               =\n|population_density_blank1_km2   =  \n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               =\n|utc_offset             =\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|21|52|9|N|33|44|52|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|footnotes                  =\n|image_flag = |leader_title = |leader_name = |government_type = \n}}\n[[File:Egypt Sudan claims.svg|thumb|right|Simplified map showing Egypt's claim (yellow and green), Sudan's claim (blue and green), the Hala'ib Triangle (green) and Bir Tawil (the white area between Egypt and Sudan)]]\n[[File:Map of the Hala'ib Triangle and Bir Tawil in 1912.png|alt=|left|thumb|Map of the Hala'ib Triangle and Bir Tawil from 1912.]]\n'''Bir Tawil''' ({{IPAc-en|b|\u026a|r|_|\u02c8|t|\u0251\u02d0|w|\u026a|l|audio=Nl-Bir Tawil.ogg}}; {{lang-arz|\u0628\u064a\u0631 \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644|translit=B\u012br \u1e6caw\u012bl|lit=tall water well}}, {{IPA-arz|bi\u02d0\u027e t\u02e4\u0251\u02c8wi\u02d0l|}}) is a {{convert|2060|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} area along the [[Egypt\u2013Sudan border|border]] between [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]], which is uninhabited and claimed by neither country. When spoken of in association with the neighbouring [[Hala'ib Triangle]], it is sometimes referred to as the '''Bir Tawil Triangle''', despite the area's [[quadrilateral]] shape; the two \"triangles\" border at a [[quadripoint]].\n\nIts ''[[terra nullius]]'' status results from a discrepancy between the straight political boundary between Egypt and Sudan established in 1899, and the irregular administrative boundary established in 1902. Egypt asserts the political boundary, and Sudan asserts the administrative boundary, with the result that the Hala'ib Triangle is claimed by both and Bir Tawil by neither. In 2014, author Alastair Bonnett described Bir Tawil as the only place on Earth that was [[habitable]] but was not claimed by any recognised government.<ref name=\"Bonnett2014\">{{cite book|last=Bonnett |first=Alastair |title=Unruly Places: Lost Spaces, Secret Cities and Other Inscrutable Geographies |chapter=Bir Tawil |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9eNJAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA73 |date=2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-544-10160-9 |page=73 |oclc=890509603 |lccn=2013050983 |quote=the only place on the planet that is both habitable and unclaimed.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 19 January 1899, an agreement between the UK and Egypt relating to the administration of the Sudan defined \"Soudan\" as the \"territories south of the 22nd parallel of latitude\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.fsu.edu:80/library/collectio/limitsinseas/ibs018.pdf|title=International Boundary Study: Sudan \u2013 Egypt (United Arab Republic) Boundary|date=27 July 1962|website=law.fsu.edu|publisher=Bureau of Intelligence and Research|pages=2, 3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113231654/http://www.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/limitsinseas/ibs018.pdf|archive-date=13 January 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref> It contained a provision that would give Egypt control of the Red Sea port of [[Suakin]], but an amendment on 10 July 1899 gave Suakin to Sudan instead.<ref name=\":0\" /> Claimed as a new independent country with the idea of independence for all. it is a monarchy that keeps the interest of its people to the number one priority.  \n\nOn 4 November 1902 the UK drew a separate \"administrative boundary\", intended to reflect the actual use of the land by the tribes in the region.<ref name=\":0\" /> Bir Tawil was grazing land used by the [[Ababda]] tribe based near [[Aswan]], and thus was placed under Egyptian administration from [[Cairo]]. Similarly, the Hala'ib Triangle to the northeast was placed under the British governor of Sudan, because its inhabitants were culturally closer to [[Khartoum]].\n\nEgypt claims the original border from 1899, the 22nd parallel, which would place the Hala'ib Triangle within Egypt and the Bir Tawil area within Sudan. Sudan, however, claims the administrative border of 1902, which would put Hala'ib within Sudan, and Bir Tawil within Egypt. As a result, both states claim the [[Hala'ib Triangle]] and neither claims the much less valuable Bir Tawil area, which is only a tenth the size, and has no permanent settlements or access to the sea. There is no basis in international law for either Sudan or Egypt to claim both territories, and neither nation is willing to cede Hala'ib. With no third state claiming the neglected area, Bir Tawil is one of the few land areas of the world [[terra nullius|not claimed by any recognised state]]. Egypt arguably still administers the territory, but it is not marked as Egyptian on government maps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcit.gov.eg/images/maps/Intl_Boundaries_map1.jpg |title=Official version of map of Egypt |accessdate=2017-03-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526181255/http://www.mcit.gov.eg/images/maps/Intl_Boundaries_map1.jpg |archive-date=2013-05-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=CIA World Factbook 2010|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pqanFyF6nI0C&pg=PA209|year=2010|publisher=CIA|chapter=Egypt}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nBir Tawil is {{convert|2060|km2|0|abbr=on}} in size. The length of its northern and southern borders are {{convert|95|km|mi}} and {{convert|46|km|mi}} respectively; the length of its eastern and western borders are {{convert|26|km|mi}} and {{convert|49|km|mi}} respectively. In the north of the area is the mountain Jabal Tawil ({{lang|ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644}}), with a height of {{convert|459|m|ft}}. In the east is [[Jebel Hagar ez Zarqa]], with a height of {{convert|662|m|ft}}. In the south is the [[Wadi]] Tawil ({{lang|ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644}}), also called ''Khawr Ab\u016b Bard''.\n\n==Climate==\n\nBir Tawil's climate is, according to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], a BWh hot, arid desert. During the summer months, approximately three-quarters of the year, temperatures can exceed {{convert|40|C}}, while its hottest three months (June\u2013August) can see it as high as {{convert|45|C|F}}. During the brief winters, however (December and January being its mildest months), Bir Tawil can experience milder temperatures with {{convert|26|C}} as its usual temperature peak.\n\nBecause the territory is far from the ocean (being at least {{cvt|200|km}} away from the [[Red Sea]]), the [[Diurnal temperature variation|diurnal temperature range]] throughout the region is large, varying from {{convert|18|to|20|\u00b0C-change|\u00b0F-change}}, year-round.<ref>[https://www.meteoblue.com/en/weather/forecast/modelclimate/21.815N33.856E \"Climate: Bir Tawil]</ref>{{Weather box|location=Bir Tawil|metric first=yes|single line=yes|Jan high C=33|Feb high C=35|Mar high C=39|Apr high C=42|May high C=44|Jun high C=45|Jul high C=45|Aug high C=45|Sep high C=44|Oct high C=41|Nov high C=36|Dec high C=32|Jan low C=1|Feb low C=2|Mar low C=4|Apr low C=9|May low C=15|Jun low C=18|Jul low C=21|Aug low C=22|Sep low C=19|Oct low C=13|Nov low C=8|Dec low C=3|source 1=''MeteoBlue.com''<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.meteoblue.com/en/weather/historyclimate/climatemodelled/21.815N33.856E393_Africa%2FCairo \n |title=Weather for Bir Tawil \n |accessdate=6 November 2019 \n |publisher=MeteoBlue.com \n |url-status=\n |archiveurl=\n |archivedate=\n}}</ref>}}\n\n==Claims==\n<!-- This has been discussed on the Talk Page. PLEASE only add any further claims to Bir Tawil AS A REFERENCE at the end of this sentence, unless it has actually solved Egypt and Sudan's border dispute. -->Due to its status as ''[[de jure]]'' unclaimed territory, a number of individuals and organizations have attempted to [[land claim|claim]] Bir Tawil as a [[micronation]]. However, none has been taken seriously by the international community, and due to the remoteness and hostile climate of the region, the vast majority of these claims have been by declarations posted online from other locations. None of these claims, or any others, have been recognized, officially or otherwise, by any government or international organization.<ref name=\"shenker030316\">{{cite news| last1=Shenker |first1=Jack |title=Welcome to the land that no country wants |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/03/welcome-to-the-land-that-no-country-wants-bir-tawil |accessdate=3 March 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_Heaton\">{{cite news |last=Liston |first=Enjoli |date=16 July 2014 |title=American plans to use his piece of Africa for advancement of science  |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/16/american-claim-africa-science-jeremiah-heaton-egypt-sudan  |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=16 Oct 2017}}</ref>{{clear left}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Egypt\u2013Sudan border]]\n* [[Egypt\u2013Sudan relations]]\n* [[Hala'ib Triangle]], an adjoining area, claimed by both Egypt and Sudan\n* [[Wadi Halfa Salient]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bir Tawil}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://googlesightseeing.com/2009/11/bir-tawil-triangle/ Google Sightseeing - Bir Tawil Triangle]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160813142038/http://archive.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/limitsinseas/IBS018.pdf International Boundary Study]\n\n{{Countries and territories of North Africa}}\n\n[[Category:Egypt\u2013Sudan border]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Egypt]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Sudan]]\n", "text_old": "{{redirect|Kingdom of North Sudan|other areas considered North Sudan|Sudan}}\n{{short description|Unclaimed land in Africa}}\n{{Infobox settlement\n<!--See the Table at Infobox Settlement for all fields and descriptions of usage-->\n<!-- Basic info  ---------------->\n|name                   = Bir Tawil\n|other_name             =\n|native_name            =  {{lang|ar|\u0628\u064a\u0631 \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644}}\n|nickname               =\n|settlement_type        = Unclaimed land\n|motto                  =\n<!-- images and maps  ----------->\n|image_skyline          = File:Topographic Map of Bir Tawil.png\n|imagesize              = 250px\n|image_caption          =[[Topographic map]] of Bir Tawil (highlighted in red)\n|image_map              =\n|mapsize                =\n|map_caption            =\n|pushpin_map            = Egypt#Sudan<!-- the name of a location map as per http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Location_map -->\n|pushpin_label_position = bottom\n|pushpin_mapsize        = 300\n|pushpin_map_caption    = Location between Egypt and Sudan\n|pushpin_map_alt        = Neither Egypt nor Sudan claim Bir Tawil, which is located between the two countries.\n<!-- Location ------------------>\n|subdivision_type       = Country\n|subdivision_name       = [[Terra nullius|None]]\n|subdivision_type1      =\n|subdivision_name1      =\n|subdivision_type2      =\n|subdivision_name2      =\n|subdivision_type3      =\n|subdivision_name3      =\n<!-- Area    --------------------->\n|area_magnitude           =\n|unit_pref                = metric\n|area_footnotes           =\n|area_total_km2           = 2060\n|area_land_km2            = <!--See table @ Template:Infobox Settlement for details on automatic unit conversion-->\n<!-- Population   ----------------------->\n|population_as_of                = 2018\n|population_footnotes            =\n|population_note                 = No permanent populations.\n|population_total                = 0\n|population_density_sq_mi        = \n|population_metro                = \n|population_density_metro_km2    =\n|population_density_metro_sq_mi  =\n|population_blank1_title         = Ethnicities\n|population_blank1               =\n|population_density_blank1_km2   =  \n|population_density_blank1_sq_mi =\n<!-- General information  --------------->\n|timezone               =\n|utc_offset             =\n|timezone_DST           =\n|utc_offset_DST         = \n|coordinates            = {{coord|21|52|9|N|33|44|52|E|type:landmark|display=inline,title}}\n|elevation_footnotes    =  <!--for references: use <ref> </ref> tags-->\n|elevation_m            =\n|elevation_ft           =\n<!-- Area/postal codes & others -------->\n|footnotes                  =\n|image_flag = |leader_title = |leader_name = |government_type = \n}}\n[[File:Egypt Sudan claims.svg|thumb|right|Simplified map showing Egypt's claim (yellow and green), Sudan's claim (blue and green), the Hala'ib Triangle (green) and Bir Tawil (the white area between Egypt and Sudan)]]\n[[File:Map of the Hala'ib Triangle and Bir Tawil in 1912.png|alt=|left|thumb|Map of the Hala'ib Triangle and Bir Tawil from 1912.]]\n'''Bir Tawil''' ({{IPAc-en|b|\u026a|r|_|\u02c8|t|\u0251\u02d0|w|\u026a|l|audio=Nl-Bir Tawil.ogg}}; {{lang-arz|\u0628\u064a\u0631 \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644|translit=B\u012br \u1e6caw\u012bl|lit=tall water well}}, {{IPA-arz|bi\u02d0\u027e t\u02e4\u0251\u02c8wi\u02d0l|}}) is a {{convert|2060|km2|mi2|abbr=on}} area along the [[Egypt\u2013Sudan border|border]] between [[Egypt]] and [[Sudan]], which is uninhabited and claimed by neither country. When spoken of in association with the neighbouring [[Hala'ib Triangle]], it is sometimes referred to as the '''Bir Tawil Triangle''', despite the area's [[quadrilateral]] shape; the two \"triangles\" border at a [[quadripoint]].\n\nIts ''[[terra nullius]]'' status results from a discrepancy between the straight political boundary between Egypt and Sudan established in 1899, and the irregular administrative boundary established in 1902. Egypt asserts the political boundary, and Sudan asserts the administrative boundary, with the result that the Hala'ib Triangle is claimed by both and Bir Tawil by neither. In 2014, author Alastair Bonnett described Bir Tawil as the only place on Earth that was [[habitable]] but was not claimed by any recognised government.<ref name=\"Bonnett2014\">{{cite book|last=Bonnett |first=Alastair |title=Unruly Places: Lost Spaces, Secret Cities and Other Inscrutable Geographies |chapter=Bir Tawil |chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=9eNJAQAAQBAJ&pg=PA73 |date=2014 |publisher=Houghton Mifflin Harcourt |isbn=978-0-544-10160-9 |page=73 |oclc=890509603 |lccn=2013050983 |quote=the only place on the planet that is both habitable and unclaimed.}}</ref>\n\n==History==\nOn 19 January 1899, an agreement between the UK and Egypt relating to the administration of the Sudan defined \"Soudan\" as the \"territories south of the 22nd parallel of latitude\".<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.law.fsu.edu:80/library/collectio/limitsinseas/ibs018.pdf|title=International Boundary Study: Sudan \u2013 Egypt (United Arab Republic) Boundary|date=27 July 1962|website=law.fsu.edu|publisher=Bureau of Intelligence and Research|pages=2, 3|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140113231654/http://www.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/limitsinseas/ibs018.pdf|archive-date=13 January 2014|url-status=dead|access-date=2019-05-28}}</ref> It contained a provision that would give Egypt control of the Red Sea port of [[Suakin]], but an amendment on 10 July 1899 gave Suakin to Sudan instead.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nOn 4 November 1902 the UK drew a separate \"administrative boundary\", intended to reflect the actual use of the land by the tribes in the region.<ref name=\":0\" /> Bir Tawil was grazing land used by the [[Ababda]] tribe based near [[Aswan]], and thus was placed under Egyptian administration from [[Cairo]]. Similarly, the Hala'ib Triangle to the northeast was placed under the British governor of Sudan, because its inhabitants were culturally closer to [[Khartoum]].\n\nEgypt claims the original border from 1899, the 22nd parallel, which would place the Hala'ib Triangle within Egypt and the Bir Tawil area within Sudan. Sudan, however, claims the administrative border of 1902, which would put Hala'ib within Sudan, and Bir Tawil within Egypt. As a result, both states claim the [[Hala'ib Triangle]] and neither claims the much less valuable Bir Tawil area, which is only a tenth the size, and has no permanent settlements or access to the sea. There is no basis in international law for either Sudan or Egypt to claim both territories, and neither nation is willing to cede Hala'ib. With no third state claiming the neglected area, Bir Tawil is one of the few land areas of the world [[terra nullius|not claimed by any recognised state]]. Egypt arguably still administers the territory, but it is not marked as Egyptian on government maps.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mcit.gov.eg/images/maps/Intl_Boundaries_map1.jpg |title=Official version of map of Egypt |accessdate=2017-03-05 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130526181255/http://www.mcit.gov.eg/images/maps/Intl_Boundaries_map1.jpg |archive-date=2013-05-26 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite book|title=CIA World Factbook 2010|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pqanFyF6nI0C&pg=PA209|year=2010|publisher=CIA|chapter=Egypt}}</ref>\n\n==Geography==\nBir Tawil is {{convert|2060|km2|0|abbr=on}} in size. The length of its northern and southern borders are {{convert|95|km|mi}} and {{convert|46|km|mi}} respectively; the length of its eastern and western borders are {{convert|26|km|mi}} and {{convert|49|km|mi}} respectively. In the north of the area is the mountain Jabal Tawil ({{lang|ar|\u062c\u0628\u0644 \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644}}), with a height of {{convert|459|m|ft}}. In the east is [[Jebel Hagar ez Zarqa]], with a height of {{convert|662|m|ft}}. In the south is the [[Wadi]] Tawil ({{lang|ar|\u0648\u0627\u062f\u064a \u0637\u0648\u064a\u0644}}), also called ''Khawr Ab\u016b Bard''.\n\n==Climate==\n\nBir Tawil's climate is, according to the [[K\u00f6ppen climate classification]], a BWh hot, arid desert. During the summer months, approximately three-quarters of the year, temperatures can exceed {{convert|40|C}}, while its hottest three months (June\u2013August) can see it as high as {{convert|45|C|F}}. During the brief winters, however (December and January being its mildest months), Bir Tawil can experience milder temperatures with {{convert|26|C}} as its usual temperature peak.\n\nBecause the territory is far from the ocean (being at least {{cvt|200|km}} away from the [[Red Sea]]), the [[Diurnal temperature variation|diurnal temperature range]] throughout the region is large, varying from {{convert|18|to|20|\u00b0C-change|\u00b0F-change}}, year-round.<ref>[https://www.meteoblue.com/en/weather/forecast/modelclimate/21.815N33.856E \"Climate: Bir Tawil]</ref>{{Weather box|location=Bir Tawil|metric first=yes|single line=yes|Jan high C=33|Feb high C=35|Mar high C=39|Apr high C=42|May high C=44|Jun high C=45|Jul high C=45|Aug high C=45|Sep high C=44|Oct high C=41|Nov high C=36|Dec high C=32|Jan low C=1|Feb low C=2|Mar low C=4|Apr low C=9|May low C=15|Jun low C=18|Jul low C=21|Aug low C=22|Sep low C=19|Oct low C=13|Nov low C=8|Dec low C=3|source 1=''MeteoBlue.com''<ref>{{cite web\n |url=https://www.meteoblue.com/en/weather/historyclimate/climatemodelled/21.815N33.856E393_Africa%2FCairo \n |title=Weather for Bir Tawil \n |accessdate=6 November 2019 \n |publisher=MeteoBlue.com \n |url-status=\n |archiveurl=\n |archivedate=\n}}</ref>}}\n\n==Claims==\n<!-- This has been discussed on the Talk Page. PLEASE only add any further claims to Bir Tawil AS A REFERENCE at the end of this sentence, unless it has actually solved Egypt and Sudan's border dispute. -->Due to its status as ''[[de jure]]'' unclaimed territory, a number of individuals and organizations have attempted to [[land claim|claim]] Bir Tawil as a [[micronation]]. However, none has been taken seriously by the international community, and due to the remoteness and hostile climate of the region, the vast majority of these claims have been by declarations posted online from other locations. None of these claims, or any others, have been recognized, officially or otherwise, by any government or international organization.<ref name=\"shenker030316\">{{cite news| last1=Shenker |first1=Jack |title=Welcome to the land that no country wants |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/mar/03/welcome-to-the-land-that-no-country-wants-bir-tawil |accessdate=3 March 2016 |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |date=3 March 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"Guardian_Heaton\">{{cite news |last=Liston |first=Enjoli |date=16 July 2014 |title=American plans to use his piece of Africa for advancement of science  |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2014/jul/16/american-claim-africa-science-jeremiah-heaton-egypt-sudan  |newspaper=[[The Guardian]] |location=London |accessdate=16 Oct 2017}}</ref>{{clear left}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Egypt\u2013Sudan border]]\n* [[Egypt\u2013Sudan relations]]\n* [[Hala'ib Triangle]], an adjoining area, claimed by both Egypt and Sudan\n* [[Wadi Halfa Salient]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Bir Tawil}}\n{{Wikivoyage}}\n* [http://googlesightseeing.com/2009/11/bir-tawil-triangle/ Google Sightseeing - Bir Tawil Triangle]\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20160813142038/http://archive.law.fsu.edu/library/collection/limitsinseas/IBS018.pdf International Boundary Study]\n\n{{Countries and territories of North Africa}}\n\n[[Category:Egypt\u2013Sudan border]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Egypt]]\n[[Category:Territorial disputes of Sudan]]\n", "name_user": "KingdomOfNavidia", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Bir_Tawil"}
{"title_page": "The Forgotten Army - Azaadi Ke Liye", "text_new": "{{short description|Indian web series}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=August 2019}}\n{{Infobox television\n| show_name                = The Forgotten Army\n| image                    =\n| caption                  = \n| genre                    = \n| based_on                 = \n| runtime                  = 30-45 Minutes\n| creator                  = Kabir Khan\n| director                 = [[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]]\n| starring                 = {{Plainlist|\n* [[Sunny Kaushal]]\n* Sharvari \n}}\n| writer                   = \n| narrated                 = [[Shah Rukh Khan]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.dnaindia.com/bollywood/report-shah-rukh-khan-turns-narrator-for-kabir-khan-s-the-forgotten-army-2808006|title=Shah Rukh Khan turns narrator for Kabir Khan's The Forgotten Army?|date=4 January 2020|website=DNA India}}</ref>\n| theme_music_composer     = [[Pritam]]\n| composer                 = Pritam \n| country                  = India\n| language                 = Hindi\n| location                 = India\n| cinematography           = \n| editor                   = \n| network                  = [[Amazon Video]]\n| picture_format           = [[Ultra HD]]\n| released                 = \n| first_aired              = {{Start date|df=y|2020|1|24}}\n| last_aired               = \n| company                  = Kabir Khan Films Pvt. Ltd\n| distributor              = \n}}\n'''The Forgotten Army - Azaadi Ke Liye''' is a web television series which premiered on [[Amazon Prime Video]] on 24 January 2020. The series is directed by [[Kabir Khan (director)|Kabir Khan]], the series is based on true events about the men and women in the [[Indian National Army]] (INA) led by [[Subhas Chandra Bose|Netaji]][[Netaji Subhas Chandra Bose| Subhash Chandra Bose]].<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/the-forgotten-army-azaadi-ke-liye-trailer-sees-sunny-kaushal-sharvari-lead-ina-wage-war-against-british-rule-7871341.html|title=The Forgotten Army: Azaadi Ke Liye trailer sees Sunny Kaushal, Sharvari lead INA, wage war against British rule|last=|first=|date=7 January 2020|website=Firstpost|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The series stars [[Sunny Kaushal]] and Sharvari.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thestatesman.com/entertainment/television/kabir-khan-make-web-series-boses-indian-national-army-1502834957.html|title=Kabir Khan to make web series on Bose's Indian National Army|last=|first=|date=18 December 2019|website=The Statesman|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> Kabir Khan made his directorial debut with a documentary titled ''The Forgotten Army'' in 1999 which was aired by [[Doordarshan]]; and during a promotional talk, Kabir Khan said the current series is a project that is 20 years in the making, based on his initial documentary.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.mid-day.com/articles/kabir-khan-project-was-in-the-making-for-20-years/22290178|title=Kabir Khan on The Forgotten Army - Azaadi Ke Liye: Project was in the making for 20 years|last=|first=|date=19 December 2019|website=Mid-Day|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/binge-watch/story/the-forgotten-army-sunny-kaushal-and-sharvari-shine-in-the-trailer-watch-video-1634711-2020-01-07|title=The Forgotten Army: Sunny Kaushal and Sharvari shine in the trailer|last=|first=|date=7 January 2020|website=India Today|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-01-10}}</ref> The trailer released on 7 January 2020.<ref name=\":1\" /> The shooting took place in locations such as Thailand, Singapore, Malaysia and Mumbai.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n==Synopsis==\nThe Forgotten Army \u2013 Azaadi Ke Liye, is based on the true story of Indian soldiers who marched towards the capital, with the war cry 'Challo Dilli', to free their country from the reign of the British. The Indian National Army (INA), which was forged out of British defeat in Singapore during WWII,  was led by the charismatic Netaji Subhash Chandra Bose and had the first women's infantry regiment since the Russian units of 1917\u20131918.<ref name=\":6\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.indiatoday.in/binge-watch/story/sunny-kaushal-and-sharvari-are-leads-in-kabir-khan-s-web-series-the-forgotten-army-1628965-2019-12-17|title=Sunny Kaushal and Sharvari are leads in Kabir Khan's web series The Forgotten Army|last=|first=|date=17 December 2019|website=Indiatoday|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2019-12-17}}</ref> While these soldiers (men and women) fought against all odds and against the British army to free India, their struggle and story somehow got lost and they became 'the forgotten army'. With the love story between two soldiers - Sodhi and Maya at the heart of it, the series raises several questions about identity, independence and the idea of motherland and the cost of freedom. Freedom, that we often take for granted but freedom that costs countless lives and sacrifices. Fighting to keep freedom alive is often more difficult than fighting to gain freedom.\n\n==Cast==\n*[[Sunny Kaushal]] as Lieutenant Sodhi<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/web-series/the-forgotten-army-sunny-kaushal-historical-genre-entertain-and-educate-the-audience-6231327/|title=The Forgotten Army actor Sunny Kaushal: Historical genre can entertain and educate the audience|date=2020-01-24|website=The Indian Express|language=en-US|access-date=2020-01-28}}</ref>\n*[[M. K. Raina]] as Old Sodhi<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.express.co.uk/showbiz/tv-radio/1232622/The-Forgotten-Army-cast-Amazon-series-Sunny-Kaushal-Rohit-Chaudhary-Sharvari-Wagh|title=The Forgotten Army cast: Who is in the cast of The Forgotten Army?|first=Neela|last=Debnath|date=27 January 2020|website=Express.co.uk}}</ref>\n*Sharvari Wagh as Maya\n* Rohit Choudhary as Arshad<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*TJ Bhanu as Rasamma<ref name=\"auto\"/>\n*Karanvir Malhotra as Amar <ref name=\"auto1\">{{Cite web|url=https://www.republicworld.com/entertainment-news/television-news/kabirs-singhs-the-forgotten-armys-cast-details|title='The Forgotten Army' boasts of a stellar cast; from Sunny Kaushal to Sharvari Wagh|first=Republic|last=World|website=Republic World}}</ref>\n*R Badree as Rajan<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*Paloma Monnappa as Rani<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Shruti Seth]] as Lakshmi<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Akhil Iyer]] as Shridhar<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*Toshiji Takeshima as Daichi<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Amala Akkineni]] as Maya's Mother<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n*[[Nizhalgal Ravi]] As Maya's Father<ref name=\"auto1\"/>\n\n== Critical reception ==\n[[The New Indian Express|''The New Indian Express'']] writes that the movie is filled with heartfelt nationalism but falls short on depth.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newindianexpress.com/entertainment/hindi/2020/jan/25/review-the-forgotten-army---azaadi-ke-liye-yes-but-for-us-2094538.html|title=Review: The Forgotten Army - Azaadi Ke Liye, yes, but for us?|last=M|first=Narayani|date=25 January 2020|website=The New Indian Express|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref> Pratishruti Ganguly writes in the ''[[Firstpost]]'' that the short series has good performances by numerous actors as well as excellent camera-work, both contributing to a worthwhile cinematic experience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/the-forgotten-army-review-kabir-khans-maiden-digital-venture-has-noble-intentions-but-is-let-down-by-its-lack-of-subtlety-7950131.html|title=The Forgotten Army review: Kabir Khan's maiden digital venture has noble intentions, but is let down by its lack of subtlety- Entertainment News, Firstpost|last=Ganguly|first=Pratishruti|date=2020-01-25|website=Firstpost|language