[Firstpost]]'' that the short series has good performances by numerous actors as well as excellent camera-work, both contributing to a worthwhile cinematic experience.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.firstpost.com/entertainment/the-forgotten-army-review-kabir-khans-maiden-digital-venture-has-noble-intentions-but-is-let-down-by-its-lack-of-subtlety-7950131.html|title=The Forgotten Army review: Kabir Khan's maiden digital venture has noble intentions, but is let down by its lack of subtlety- Entertainment News, Firstpost|last=Ganguly|first=Pratishruti|date=2020-01-25|website=Firstpost|language=en|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-02-18}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External link==\n* {{IMDb title|id=10289938}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Forgotten Army - Azaadi Ke Liye}}\n[[Category:Amazon Video original programming]]\n[[Category:2020 Indian television series debuts]]\n[[Category:Indian National Army in fiction]]\n[[Category:2020s Indian television miniseries]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Singapore]]\n[[Category:Television series set in 1996]]\n[[Category:Television series set in the 1940s]]\n[[Category:Cultural depictions of Subhas Chandra Bose]]\n[[Category:Television shows set in Myanmar]]\n\n{{India-tv-prog-stub}}\n", "name_user": "2409:4060:2089:b5fe:85b1:a9a:6f2a:8672", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Forgotten_Army_-_Azaadi_Ke_Liye"}
{"title_page": "Paulette Flint", "text_new": "{{Multiple issues|\n{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2018}}\n}}\n\n{{subst:unreviewed}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name            = Paulette Sybil Flint\n| other_names     = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             =\n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Gladstone, Queensland]], Australia\n| occupation      = \n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       = \n| nationality     = [[Australian]]\n| genre           = \n| influences      =\n| influenced      = \n| footnotes       =\n| updated         = \n}}\n\n'''Paulette Sybil Flint''' (born 25 November 1953) is a local historian and author in [[Gladstone, Queensland]], Australia and is an independent history columnist for [[The Observer (Gladstone)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/surprising-history-behind-your-gladstone-street-na/3798476/|title=Surprising history behind your Gladstone street name|last=Harris|first=Matt|date=6 Aug 2019|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nPaulette Sybil Flint was born in [[Gladstone, Queensland]] in 1953. She was the daughter of Frederick Allan Fohrman (Shop Assistant) and Sybil Beatrice Fohrman, nee Barker. Paulette was educated at Gladstone Central State School and [[Gladstone State High School]] and graduated in 1970. Paulette married Raymond Flint (Electrician) in 1973 in Gladstone. They had three children; Dr Nicole Flint in 1979, Megan Lennon (nee Flint) in 1982 and Kate Flint in 1989.\n\n== Education and career ==\nOn graduation from Gladstone State High School,<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://trove.nla.gov.au/work/9381942?q&versionId=10883564|title=\"TONKA 1970\", Gladstone State High School Annual Yearbook|last=|first=|date=1970|website=Trove|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=20 November 2019}}</ref> Flint won a State Scholarship and then went on to graduate with a Diploma of Teaching (Dip. T) from Kedron Park Teachers College in 1973.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://digitalcollections.qut.edu.au/3591/|title=Graduands Kedron Park Teachers College 1973|last=|first=|date=|website=QUT Digital Collections|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=1973|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> Flint taught at Gladstone Central State School and [[Hamilton Island (Queensland)|Hamilton Island]] State School (1986-1988). Flint graduated from [[Central Queensland University]] in 1993 with a [[Bachelor of Education]] (B.Ed.) and obtained a Graduate Diploma in Local, Family and Applied History from the [[University of New England (Australia)|University of New England]] (UNE) in 2007. Flint also taught at Toolooa State High School in Gladstone and Benaraby State School in [[Benaraby]]. She then transferred to Kin Kora State School, Gladstone, where she taught lower school and acted in the capacity of Key Teacher for the Year 2 Net. Flint attended the Summer School for Teachers in January 2007 which was seen by the Australian Government as a reward for high-achieving teachers. Attendees received a bonus payment.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aph.gov.au/About_Parliament/Parliamentary_Departments/Parliamentary_Library/pubs/rp/BudgetReview_2007-_2008/Eduction|title=Budget Review 2007-2008 Education|last=Missingham|first=Roxanne|date=21 May 2017|website=Parliament of Australia|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=18 November 2019}}</ref> In 2007 she was employed at Kin Kora State School as Special Education Teacher, and was promoted to Head of Department (Head of Special Education Services) at Kin Kora State School, Gladstone. She was employed in this position by [[Education Queensland]]. from January 2013 until her retirement in 2015.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://kinkorass.eq.edu.au/Calendarandnews/Newsletters/Newsletters/newsletter-2015-03-31.pdf|title=Kin Kora State School Newsletter|last=|first=|date=31 March 2015|website=Kin Kora State School|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Community involvement ==\nFlint joined the [https://www.gladstonecommunitydirectory.com.au/organisation.cfm?OID=277 Genealogical Society Gladstone District Incorporated] (then known as Genealogical Society of Queensland, Gladstone branch) early in 1992 and has held various management committee positions from 1992\u2013present. She conducts regular Genealogical Workshops for the Genealogical Society, including an annual Beginners\u2019 Workshop.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/who-do-you-think-you-are-this-event-will-help-you-/3674985/|title=Who do you think you are? This event will help you find out|last=Gillani|first=Noor|date=19 Mar 2019|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\u00a0She is a regular guest speaker on the history of the Gladstone Region, or on Genealogy. At the  [http://www.gladstonelibraries.qld.gov.au/ Gladstone City Library] she has spoken on local history via \u201c''Words of Wisdom''\u201d in March 2016 <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/the-observer-8995/20160312/281638189307799|title=All About Women|last=Norris|first=Sue|date=12 March 2016|work=PressReader, The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/the-observer-8995/20160307/281578059755631|title=Gladstone women offer their wisdom as what's good for her is great for us|last=|first=|date=7 March 2016|work=PressReader, The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> and on Genealogy in May 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.westernstarnews.com.au/news/how-to-shake-your-family-tree/3415651/|title=Researchers top tips to trace your family tree|last=Bray|first=Bray Gregory|date=16 May 2018|work=The Western Star|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>  Flint, along with other Genealogical Society volunteers Judy Spencer and Jan Koivunen conducted a walk titled \"''Tales from Yesteryear''\" in the Gladstone Cemetery in November 2018.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/tales-from-yesteryear-as-old-cemetery-comes-to-lif/3583556/|title=Tales from yesteryear as old cemetery comes to life|last=Bray|first=Gregory|date=24 Nov 2018|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nFlint was employed as a Master Class Teacher for \u201c''Our Priceless Past''\u201d<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.foreveryoungautobiographies.com/our-priceless-past/|title=Case study: Students interview seniors for Our Priceless Past lift-out and expo|last=Gray|first=Nicola|date=26 September 2019|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> events at the [[Gladstone Regional Art Gallery and Museum]] from 2015-2019. For 21 years, this annual community event has involved students interviewing and writing the life stories of seniors over the age of 70, who have lived in the Gladstone area for over 30 years. The stories are printed in a collectors\u2019 section of The Observer (Gladstone) and are displayed with photos and memorabilia from the seniors at the exhibition at the Gladstone Regional Art Gallery and Museum. In this role, Flint assists school students to interview the seniors and write articles for the exhibition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://issuu.com/armcustompublishing/docs/our_pricesless_past_-_gladstone|title=Our Priceless Past - Gladstone Observer. Seniors 2017 official supplement|last=|first=|date=20 Sep 2017|website=issuu|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.pressreader.com/australia/the-observer-8995/20190619/281891594798838|title=Our Priceless Past|last=Paddick|first=Di|date=20 June 2019|work=PressReader, The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://gragm.qld.gov.au/exhibitions/2019-our-priceless-past|title=2019 Our Priceless Past|last=|first=|date=17 August 2019|website=Gladstone Regional Art Gallery & Museum|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nFlint is regularly consulted when local history information is sought <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.dailymercury.com.au/news/properties-snapped-up-suburbs-no-one-heard-of/1854021/|title=Properties snapped up in suburbs no-one has heard of|last=KIRVING|first=|date=6 May 2013|work=Daily Mercury|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> and was involved in research for some local mysteries, such as finding the descendants of Reverend John Campbell after his 100-year-old diary was discovered in a charity bin in Gladstone in 2012.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.coolum-news.com.au/news/discovery-leads-to-intrigue-diary-john-campbell/1316922/|title=Discovery leads to intrigue|last=Lanzon|first=Ren|date=26 Mar 2012|work=Coolum & North Shore News|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> Flint assisted in locating living relatives of one of the Australian soldiers who had left graffiti in the Naour tunnels on the Western Front. Gilles Prilaux, a French archaeologist was seeking this information for his book.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/genealogical-society-secretarys-investigation-pays/3537593/|title=Genealogical society secretary's investigation pays off|last=Bray|first=Gregory|date=1 Oct 2018|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/historic-signature-of-gladstone-soldier-found-in-f/3537596/#/0|title=Historic signature of Gladstone soldier found in French cave|last=Bray|first=Gregory|date=1 Oct 2018|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Published articles ==\nCommencing in 1994, Flint writes regular articles about the history of the Gladstone Region for the Observer (Gladstone) under the category of \u201c''Times Gone By''\u201d. These articles are also published by other newspapers in the News Corp Syndicate.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.northernstar.com.au/news/times-gone-by-boyne-valley-cwa-gets-its-own-home/3616475/|title=Times Gone By: Boyne Valley CWA gets its own home|last=|first=|date=8 Jan 2019|work=Northern Star|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\nSample of Articles:\n\n* \"Times Gone By: 'Tis the season for dancing at balls\" (2015)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/july-211908-social-engagements-have-been-fairly-nu/2712105/|title=Times Gone By: 'Tis the season for dancing at balls|last=Flint|first=Paulette|date=21 Jul 2015|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n* \"1949 Cyclone\" (As published in Gladstone Observer, 2 March 2016)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://gladstonehistoryinc.wordpress.com/1949-cyclone/|title=1949 Cyclone (As published in Gladstone Observer, 2 March, 2016)|last=Flint|first=Paulette|date=2 March 2016|website=HistoryInc|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n*\"Gladstone flashback: Explosions and unforgettable deaths (2018) <ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.qt.com.au/news/gladstone-flashback-explosions-and-unforgettable-d/3525571/|title=Gladstone flashback: Explosions and unforgettable deaths|last=Flint|first=Paulette|date=19 Sep 2018|work=The Queensland Times|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n* \"Flashback: Reflections of Christmases gone by\" (2018)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/flashback-reflections-of-christmases-gone-by/3610187/|title=Flashback: Reflections of Christmases gone by|last=Flint|first=Paulette|date=28 Dec 2018|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref> \n* \"Times Gone By: Adrift boat in danger of sinking\" (2019)<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/times-gone-by-adrift-boat-in-danger-of-sinking/3720863/|title=Times Gone By: Adrift boat in danger of sinking|last=Flint|first=Paulette|date=8 May 2019|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Published books==\n''[https://catalogue.nla.gov.au/Record/4705642 What\u2019s in a Name? The stories behind the street names of Gladstone, Queensland]'', published in December 2009 (HistoryInc) {{ISBN|9780980709308}}\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{Improve categories|date=February 2020}}\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Flint, Paulette}}\n[[Category:Australian historians]]\n[[Category:1953 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{subst:unreviewed}}\n{{BLP sources|date=December 2018}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2018}}\n{{Use Australian English|date=April 2018}}\n{{Infobox writer\n| name            = Paulette Sybil Flint\n| other_names     = \n| image           = \n| image_size      = \n| alt             =\n| caption         = \n| birth_name      = \n| birth_date      = {{Birth date and age|1953|11|25|df=y}}\n| birth_place     = [[Gladstone, Queensland]], Australia\n| occupation      = \n| death_date      =\n| death_place     =\n| death_cause     =\n| residence       = \n| nationality     = [[Australian]]\n| genre           = \n| influences      =\n| influenced      = \n| footnotes       =\n| updated         = \n}}\n\n'''Paulette Sybil Flint''' (born 25th November 1953) is a local historian and author in [[Gladstone, Queensland]], Australia and is an independent history columnist for [[The Observer (Gladstone)]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.gladstoneobserver.com.au/news/surprising-history-behind-your-gladstone-street-na/3798476/|title=Surprising history behind your Gladstone street name|last=Harris|first=Matt|date=6 Aug 2019|work=The Observer (Gladstone)|access-date=30 October 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nPaulette Sybil Flint was born in [[Gladstone, Queensland]] in 1953. She was